<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 3 · Lesson 3.11</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Parabolas & Vertex Form</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Learn to read the vertex, axis of symmetry, direction, and intercepts of a parabola from its equation — in both standard and vertex form — without graphing.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Two forms of a quadratic — what each reveals</div>
  <div class="body-text">The same parabola can be written in different forms. Each form makes certain features immediately visible. The SAT will switch between forms and ask you to identify key features — know what each form tells you at a glance.</div>
  <div class="forms-grid">
    <div class="form-card" style="background:#F5F3FF;">
      <div class="form-title" style="color:#4C1D95;">Standard Form</div>
      <div class="form-eq">f(x) = ax² + bx + c</div>
      <div class="form-body">Best for reading the y-intercept (c) and the direction (sign of a).</div>
      <div class="form-reads">
        <strong>y-intercept:</strong> x = 0 → y = c<br>
        <strong>Axis of symmetry:</strong> x = −b/(2a)<br>
        <strong>Vertex x:</strong> −b/(2a), then substitute for y<br>
        <strong>Opens up:</strong> a &gt; 0 · <strong>Opens down:</strong> a &lt; 0
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="form-card" style="background:#EDE9FE;">
      <div class="form-title" style="color:#4C1D95;">Vertex Form</div>
      <div class="form-eq">f(x) = a(x − h)² + k</div>
      <div class="form-body">Best for reading the vertex and axis of symmetry directly.</div>
      <div class="form-reads">
        <strong>Vertex:</strong> (h, k) — read directly<br>
        <strong>Axis of symmetry:</strong> x = h<br>
        <strong>Min/Max value:</strong> k (minimum if a&gt;0, maximum if a&lt;0)<br>
        <strong>Opens up:</strong> a &gt; 0 · <strong>Opens down:</strong> a &lt; 0
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Critical trap — vertex form sign</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      In f(x) = a(x − <strong>h</strong>)² + k, the vertex is at x = <strong>h</strong> — NOT x = −h.<br><br>
      f(x) = 2(x − <strong>3</strong>)² + 5 → vertex at (<strong>3</strong>, 5) ✓<br>
      f(x) = 2(x + <strong>3</strong>)² + 5 = 2(x − (<strong>−3</strong>))² + 5 → vertex at (<strong>−3</strong>, 5) ✓<br><br>
      When you see (x + h), rewrite as (x − (−h)) to identify the vertex correctly.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Key features at a glance</div>
  <table class="features-table">
    <tr><th>Feature</th><th>From standard form ax²+bx+c</th><th>From vertex form a(x−h)²+k</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Vertex</td><td>x = <em>−b/(2a)</em>, then find y by substituting</td><td>Directly: <em>(h, k)</em></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Axis of symmetry</td><td><em>x = −b/(2a)</em></td><td><em>x = h</em></td></tr>
    <tr><td>y-intercept</td><td>Directly: <em>(0, c)</em></td><td>Substitute x = 0: <em>a(−h)² + k = ah² + k</em></td></tr>
    <tr><td>x-intercepts (roots)</td><td>Solve <em>ax²+bx+c=0</em></td><td>Set <em>a(x−h)²+k=0</em> → <em>x = h ± √(−k/a)</em></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Minimum/Maximum</td><td>Minimum if <em>a&gt;0</em>, maximum if <em>a&lt;0</em>. Value: substitute x=−b/(2a)</td><td>Directly: <em>k</em> is the min/max value</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Direction</td><td><em>a&gt;0</em> → opens up · <em>a&lt;0</em> → opens down</td><td>Same: sign of <em>a</em></td></tr>
  </table>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Converting between forms</div>
  <div class="body-text">The SAT may give an equation in one form and ask about a feature best read from the other. Knowing how to convert quickly is essential.</div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — standard to vertex form</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      Convert f(x) = x² − 6x + 5 to vertex form.<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Step 1: Find vertex x — axis of symmetry: x = −(−6)/(2·1) = 3</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Step 2: Find vertex y — f(3) = 9 − 18 + 5 = −4</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Step 3: Vertex form: f(x) = (x − 3)² − 4</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Verify: (x−3)² − 4 = x² − 6x + 9 − 4 = x² − 6x + 5 ✓</span><br><br>
      Vertex: (3, −4) · Axis of symmetry: x = 3 · Minimum value: −4
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Vertex form → read vertex instantly</div><div class="tip-body">If the SAT gives vertex form f(x) = a(x−h)²+k, the vertex is (h, k). Don't calculate — just read it. Watch the sign: (x−3)² gives h = 3, but (x+3)² gives h = −3.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Minimum value ≠ vertex x-coordinate</div><div class="tip-body">The minimum (or maximum) value of the function is k — the y-coordinate of the vertex. The SAT frequently asks "what is the minimum value of f?" — the answer is k, not h.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Axis of symmetry from standard form</div><div class="tip-body">x = −b/(2a) is fast and always works. For f(x) = 2x²−12x+7: axis = −(−12)/(2·2) = 12/4 = 3. The vertex is at x = 3, and the minimum value is f(3).</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Number of x-intercepts from the vertex</div><div class="tip-body">If the parabola opens up (a&gt;0) and vertex is above x-axis (k&gt;0) → no x-intercepts. If vertex is on x-axis (k=0) → one. If below (k&lt;0) → two. Flip logic for a&lt;0.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

