<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 3 · Lesson 3.12</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Polynomials</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Learn to add, subtract, multiply, and factor polynomial expressions — and master the Remainder Theorem and Factor Theorem, two powerful shortcuts the SAT uses repeatedly.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Polynomial basics</div>
  <div class="body-text">A <strong>polynomial</strong> is a sum of terms, each of the form axⁿ where n is a non-negative integer. The <strong>degree</strong> is the highest power of x in the expression.</div>
  <table class="concept-table">
    <tr><th>Term</th><th>Definition</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Degree</td><td>Highest exponent in the polynomial</td><td><em>3x⁴ − 2x² + 5</em> has degree 4</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Leading coefficient</td><td>Coefficient of the highest-degree term</td><td><em>3x⁴ − 2x² + 5</em>: leading coeff = 3</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Like terms</td><td>Terms with the same variable and exponent</td><td><em>4x² and −7x²</em> are like terms</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Roots / zeros</td><td>Values of x where the polynomial equals zero</td><td>If <em>p(2) = 0</em>, then x = 2 is a root</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Factor</td><td>An expression that divides the polynomial evenly</td><td>If x = 2 is a root, then <em>(x − 2)</em> is a factor</td></tr>
  </table>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Operations on polynomials</div>
  <div class="ops-grid">
    <div class="op-card" style="background:#F5F3FF;">
      <div class="op-title" style="color:#4C1D95;">Adding & Subtracting</div>
      <div class="op-rule">Combine like terms — same degree, same variable. Watch signs when subtracting: distribute the negative to every term in the second polynomial.</div>
      <div class="op-ex">(3x² + 2x − 1) + (x² − 5x + 4)<br>= 4x² − 3x + 3<br><br>(3x² + 2x − 1) − (x² − 5x + 4)<br>= 2x² + 7x − 5</div>
    </div>
    <div class="op-card" style="background:#EDE9FE;">
      <div class="op-title" style="color:#4C1D95;">Multiplying</div>
      <div class="op-rule">Distribute every term of the first polynomial to every term of the second. Then combine like terms. Use FOIL for two binomials.</div>
      <div class="op-ex">(x + 2)(x² − 3x + 1)<br>= x³ − 3x² + x + 2x² − 6x + 2<br>= x³ − x² − 5x + 2</div>
    </div>
    <div class="op-card" style="background:#EAF3DE;">
      <div class="op-title" style="color:#27500A;">Remainder Theorem</div>
      <div class="op-rule">When polynomial p(x) is divided by (x − a), the remainder equals p(a). No long division needed — just evaluate the polynomial at x = a.</div>
      <div class="op-ex">p(x) = x³ − 2x + 5, divided by (x − 2)<br>Remainder = p(2) = 8 − 4 + 5 = 9</div>
    </div>
    <div class="op-card" style="background:#FEF3C7;">
      <div class="op-title" style="color:#92400E;">Factor Theorem</div>
      <div class="op-rule">(x − a) is a factor of p(x) if and only if p(a) = 0. To check if something is a factor, evaluate — don't divide.</div>
      <div class="op-ex">Is (x − 3) a factor of x² − 5x + 6?<br>p(3) = 9 − 15 + 6 = 0 ✓<br>Yes — (x − 3) is a factor.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — Remainder Theorem</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      If p(x) = 2x³ − x² + 3x − 7, what is the remainder when p(x) is divided by (x − 2)?<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">By the Remainder Theorem: remainder = p(2)</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">p(2) = 2(8) − (4) + 3(2) − 7</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">= 16 − 4 + 6 − 7</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">= 11</span><br><br>
      The remainder is 11. No polynomial long division needed.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Remainder Theorem saves 2 minutes</div><div class="tip-body">When the SAT asks for a remainder when dividing by (x − a), never do long division. Just evaluate p(a). If the SAT asks what value of a makes the remainder zero — that's asking for a root, so set p(a) = 0 and solve.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Factor Theorem — test by substitution</div><div class="tip-body">To check if (x − a) is a factor, substitute x = a into the polynomial. If the result is 0, it's a factor. If not, it's not. This is faster than any algebraic manipulation.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Subtract polynomials — distribute the negative</div><div class="tip-body">The most common error in polynomial subtraction: forgetting to distribute the minus sign. (3x² + 2) − (x² − 4) = 3x² + 2 − x² + 4 = 2x² + 6. Every term in the second polynomial changes sign.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Degree of product = sum of degrees</div><div class="tip-body">When multiplying two polynomials, the degree of the result equals the sum of the degrees. A degree-2 times a degree-3 gives a degree-5 polynomial. Use this to quickly check if your answer has the right leading term.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

