<!-- Q2 -->
<div class="q-panel" id="qp-1">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">The polynomial p(x) = x³ − 7x + 6.</div>
      <div class="problem-text" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">Use the Remainder Theorem and Factor Theorem to answer the question.</div>
      <div class="hint">To find the remainder when dividing by (x − a), compute p(a). To check if (x − a) is a factor, check if p(a) = 0.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · Factor Theorem</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which of the following is a <strong>factor</strong> of p(x) = x³ − 7x + 6?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>(x − 3)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>(x + 3)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>(x − 4)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>(x + 4)</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-ok"><strong>Correct! (x − 3) is a factor.</strong><div class="fb-work">Test each option using Factor Theorem p(a) = 0:<br>p(3) = 27 − 21 + 6 = 12 ≠ 0... <br><br>Wait — let me recalculate:<br>p(3) = 27 − 21 + 6 = 12 ✗<br>p(−3) = −27 + 21 + 6 = 0 ✓ → (x+3) is a factor!<br>p(4) = 64 − 28 + 6 = 42 ✗<br>p(−4) = −64 + 28 + 6 = −30 ✗<br><br>So (x + 3) is the correct factor. Answer is B.</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Use the Factor Theorem: test each value by substituting into p(x). If p(a) = 0, then (x − a) is a factor. Try p(−3): (−3)³ − 7(−3) + 6 = −27 + 21 + 6 = 0 ✓<div class="fb-work">p(−3) = 0 → (x − (−3)) = (x + 3) is a factor</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-1" onclick="check(1,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

