<div class="lesson-title">Rational Expressions</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Learn to simplify, multiply, divide, and add rational expressions — algebraic fractions — and solve rational equations by clearing denominators.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">What is a rational expression?</div>
  <div class="body-text">A <strong>rational expression</strong> is a fraction where numerator and denominator are polynomials. Rules mirror regular fractions: factor first, then simplify. The key rule: <strong>never cancel terms — only factors</strong>.</div>
  <div class="ops-grid">
    <div class="op-card" style="background:#F5F3FF;"><div class="op-title" style="color:#4C1D95;">Simplifying</div><div class="op-rule">Factor fully. Cancel common factors (not terms).</div><div class="op-ex">(x²−4)/(x+2) = (x+2)(x−2)/(x+2) = x−2</div></div>
    <div class="op-card" style="background:#EDE9FE;"><div class="op-title" style="color:#4C1D95;">Multiplying</div><div class="op-rule">Multiply numerators, multiply denominators. Factor and cancel before multiplying.</div><div class="op-ex">(x+1)/(x−3) · (x−3)/(x+2) = (x+1)/(x+2)</div></div>
    <div class="op-card" style="background:#EAF3DE;"><div class="op-title" style="color:#27500A;">Dividing</div><div class="op-rule">Multiply by the reciprocal. Flip the second fraction, then multiply.</div><div class="op-ex">(x²−1)/x ÷ (x+1)/3 = (x−1)·3/x = 3(x−1)/x</div></div>
    <div class="op-card" style="background:#FEF3C7;"><div class="op-title" style="color:#92400E;">Adding & Subtracting</div><div class="op-rule">Find LCD, rewrite each fraction with LCD, combine numerators, simplify.</div><div class="op-ex">1/x + 2/(x+1) = (x+1+2x)/[x(x+1)] = (3x+1)/[x(x+1)]</div></div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Solving a rational equation</div>
    <div class="fb-work">3/(x−2) = 5/x<br>Multiply both sides by x(x−2):<br>3x = 5(x−2) → 3x = 5x−10 → x = 5 ✓</div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="card"><div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div><div class="tips-grid">
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Factor before anything else</div><div class="tip-body">Factor every numerator and denominator before multiplying, dividing, or simplifying. This reveals what cancels and keeps arithmetic manageable.</div></div>
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Never cancel terms — only factors</div><div class="tip-body">(x+3)/(x+5) cannot simplify by cancelling x. Only cancel when the same expression is a factor in both numerator and denominator, separated by multiplication — not addition.</div></div>
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Clear denominators to solve equations</div><div class="tip-body">Multiply both sides by the LCD to eliminate all fractions. This turns a rational equation into a simple linear or quadratic equation you already know how to solve.</div></div>
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Check for extraneous solutions</div><div class="tip-body">After solving, verify no denominator equals zero at your solution. If x = 2 makes a denominator zero, discard it — it's extraneous even if it solved the algebra correctly.</div></div>
