<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 3 · Lesson 3.14</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Radicals & Rational Exponents</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master operations with square roots, cube roots, and rational exponents — and learn the conversion that connects them.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>
<div class="card"><div class="sec-title">Radical ↔ Rational exponent conversion</div>
<div class="body-text">Every radical can be rewritten as a rational (fractional) exponent. This is one of the most tested conversions on the SAT.</div>
<div class="formula-box">
<div class="formula">ⁿ√(aᵐ) = a^(m/n) &nbsp;&nbsp; a^(1/n) = ⁿ√a &nbsp;&nbsp; a^(m/n) = (ⁿ√a)ᵐ</div>
<div class="formula-sub">The denominator of the exponent = the index of the radical · The numerator = the power</div>
</div>
<div class="grid2">
<div class="mini"><div class="mini-t">Key examples</div>
<div class="mini-ex">√x = x^(1/2)<br>∛x = x^(1/3)<br>x^(2/3) = (∛x)² = ∛(x²)<br>x^(3/2) = (√x)³ = √(x³)</div></div>
<div class="mini"><div class="mini-t">Exponent rules still apply</div>
<div class="mini-ex">x^(1/2) · x^(1/2) = x¹ = x<br>x^(2/3) · x^(1/3) = x¹ = x<br>(x^(1/2))⁴ = x²<br>x^(−1/2) = 1/√x</div></div>
</div>
<div class="ex-box"><div class="ex-label">Worked example</div>
<div class="fb-work">Simplify: (8x⁶)^(2/3)<br>= 8^(2/3) · (x⁶)^(2/3)<br>= (∛8)² · x⁴<br>= 4x⁴ ✓</div></div>
</div>
<div class="card"><div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div><div class="tips-grid">
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Convert radicals to exponents first</div><div class="tip-body">When an expression mixes radicals and exponents, convert everything to rational exponent form. Then apply the standard exponent rules you already know.</div></div>
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Denominator = root, numerator = power</div><div class="tip-body">In a^(m/n): n is the root (denominator) and m is the power (numerator). For a^(2/3): take the cube root first, then square — or vice versa (same result).</div></div>
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Simplify the radicand first</div><div class="tip-body">Before taking a root, factor out perfect squares (or cubes). √(72) = √(36·2) = 6√2. The SAT always has a "clean" simplification path.</div></div>
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Negative exponents = reciprocals</div><div class="tip-body">a^(−m/n) = 1/a^(m/n). Never leave a negative exponent in a final answer unless the question asks for it. Rewrite as a fraction.</div></div>
</div></div>
