<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 3 · Lesson 3.15</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Exponential Functions</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Learn to identify, evaluate, and interpret exponential growth and decay functions — and connect the equation to real-world models like population and compound interest.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>
<div class="card"><div class="sec-title">The exponential function</div>
<div class="body-text">An <strong>exponential function</strong> has the form f(x) = a·bˣ, where b is the base (b &gt; 0, b ≠ 1). The variable is in the exponent — this makes growth or decay far faster than any linear or polynomial function.</div>
<div class="formula-box">
<div class="formula">f(x) = a · bˣ</div>
<div class="formula-sub">a = initial value (when x = 0) · b &gt; 1: growth · 0 &lt; b &lt; 1: decay</div>
</div>
<div class="grid2">
<div class="mini"><div class="mini-t" style="color:#3B6D11">Growth: b > 1</div>
<div class="mini-b">Each unit increase in x multiplies output by b. The function increases without bound.</div>
<div class="mini-ex">f(x) = 500·(1.06)ˣ<br>6% growth per period.<br>f(0)=500, f(1)=530, f(2)=561.8</div></div>
<div class="mini"><div class="mini-t" style="color:#A32D2D">Decay: 0 &lt; b &lt; 1</div>
<div class="mini-b">Each unit increase in x multiplies output by b (a fraction). The function decreases toward zero.</div>
<div class="mini-ex">f(x) = 1000·(0.8)ˣ<br>20% decrease per period.<br>f(0)=1000, f(1)=800, f(2)=640</div></div>
</div>
<div class="ex-box"><div class="ex-label">SAT model types</div>
<div class="fb-work">Growth: f(t) = a(1 + r)ᵗ where r = growth rate<br>Decay: f(t) = a(1 − r)ᵗ where r = decay rate<br>Compound interest: A = P(1 + r/n)^(nt)<br>Half-life: A = A₀·(1/2)^(t/h) where h = half-life period</div></div>
</div>
<div class="card"><div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div><div class="tips-grid">
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Initial value = f(0) = a</div><div class="tip-body">In f(x) = a·bˣ, the initial value is a because b⁰ = 1. The SAT asks "what is the initial value?" — it's always the coefficient a, not the base b.</div></div>
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Identify growth vs. decay from b</div><div class="tip-body">b &gt; 1 → growth. b between 0 and 1 → decay. For f(x) = 200·(0.75)ˣ: b = 0.75 &lt; 1 → decay. The function loses 25% of its value per period.</div></div>
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Percent change from base b</div><div class="tip-body">If b = 1.08, the quantity grows 8% per period. If b = 0.92, it decreases 8% per period. The percent change = |b − 1| × 100%. This interpretation appears constantly on the SAT.</div></div>
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Compare exponential to linear</div><div class="tip-body">The SAT may give a table and ask whether the relationship is linear or exponential. Linear: constant differences. Exponential: constant ratios. Divide consecutive y-values — if the ratio is constant, it's exponential.</div></div>
</div></div>
