<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 3 · Lesson 3.16</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Function Notation & Operations</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master function notation, domain and range, composite functions, and the transformations that shift and reflect graphs — all tested frequently on the SAT.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>
<div class="card"><div class="sec-title">Function notation essentials</div>
<div class="body-text">Functions map each input to exactly one output. The notation f(x) means "the output of function f when input is x." The SAT tests several key operations on functions.</div>
<div class="grid2">
<div class="mini"><div class="mini-t">Evaluating: f(a)</div><div class="mini-b">Substitute x = a into the function formula.</div><div class="mini-ex">f(x) = 3x − 1<br>f(4) = 3(4)−1 = 11<br>f(−2) = 3(−2)−1 = −7</div></div>
<div class="mini"><div class="mini-t">Composite: f(g(x))</div><div class="mini-b">Apply g first, then apply f to the result. Work from the inside out.</div><div class="mini-ex">f(x)=2x+1, g(x)=x²<br>f(g(3))=f(9)=2(9)+1=19<br>g(f(3))=g(7)=49</div></div>
<div class="mini"><div class="mini-t">Domain</div><div class="mini-b">All valid inputs (x-values). Exclude: values making denominators zero, or square roots of negatives.</div><div class="mini-ex">f(x)=1/(x−3): domain all x≠3<br>g(x)=√(x−2): domain x≥2</div></div>
<div class="mini"><div class="mini-t">Range</div><div class="mini-b">All possible outputs (y-values). For f(x)=x²: range is y≥0. For f(x)=|x|+1: range is y≥1.</div><div class="mini-ex">f(x)=2x+3: range all reals<br>f(x)=x²+1: range y≥1</div></div>
</div>
<div class="ex-box"><div class="ex-label">Graph transformations</div>
<div class="fb-work">f(x) + k → shift UP k units<br>f(x) − k → shift DOWN k units<br>f(x + h) → shift LEFT h units<br>f(x − h) → shift RIGHT h units<br>−f(x) → reflect over x-axis<br>f(−x) → reflect over y-axis<br>a·f(x), a>1 → vertical stretch</div></div>
</div>
<div class="card"><div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div><div class="tips-grid">
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Composite: always work inside-out</div><div class="tip-body">For f(g(x)), evaluate g(x) first, then plug that result into f. Don't try to substitute x into f directly — always resolve the inner function first.</div></div>
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">f(x+2) shifts LEFT, not right</div><div class="tip-body">This is counterintuitive. f(x+2) shifts the graph LEFT by 2. f(x−2) shifts RIGHT by 2. The sign inside the parentheses is opposite to the direction of horizontal shift.</div></div>
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Domain restrictions: set denominator ≠ 0</div><div class="tip-body">To find domain restrictions, set each denominator equal to zero and solve. Those x-values are excluded. For square roots, set the radicand ≥ 0 and solve.</div></div>
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">−f(x) flips vertically; f(−x) flips horizontally</div><div class="tip-body">The negative outside: −f(x) reflects over the x-axis (y-values flip sign). The negative inside: f(−x) reflects over the y-axis (x-values flip sign). Location of the negative determines the axis.</div></div>
</div></div>
<div class="sec-title" style="margin-bottom:.75rem">Practice questions</div>
<div class="q-tabs">
  <button class="q-tab active" onclick="switchQ(0,this)">Question 1</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(1,this)">Question 2</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(2,this)">Question 3</button>
</div>
<div class="q-panel active" id="qp-0">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">Given f(x) = x² − 3 and g(x) = 2x + 1</div>
      <span class="math-eq">Find f(g(2))</span>
      <div class="hint">Work inside-out. First find g(2), then plug that result into f. g(2) = 2(2)+1 = 5. Then f(5) = 5² − 3.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 1 · Composite Functions</div>
      <div class="q-text">What is f(g(2))?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-0"><div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>22</div><div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>5</div><div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>1</div><div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>25</div></div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-ok"><strong>Correct! f(g(2)) = 22</strong><div class='fb-work'>g(2) = 2(2)+1 = 5<br>f(g(2)) = f(5) = 5²−3 = 25−3 = 22 ✓</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Work inside-out: first compute g(2) = 2(2)+1. Then substitute that answer into f.<div class='fb-work'>g(2)=5 → f(5)=25−3=22</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-0" onclick="check(0,'A')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div><div class="q-panel " id="qp-1">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">The graph of f(x) is shifted 3 units right and 2 units down.</div>
      <span class="math-eq">New function: f(x − 3) − 2</span>
      <div class="hint">Right shift h units → replace x with (x−h). Down k units → subtract k from the whole function. Right 3 → (x−3). Down 2 → −2.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · Transformations</div>
      <div class="q-text">If f(x) = x², what is the equation of the transformed graph?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1"><div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>(x+3)² + 2</div><div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>(x−3)² + 2</div><div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>(x−3)² − 2</div><div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>(x+3)² − 2</div></div>
