<div class="card"><div class="sec-title">Ratios, rates, and proportions</div>
<div class="body-text">A <strong>ratio</strong> compares two quantities. A <strong>proportion</strong> states that two ratios are equal. Cross-multiplication is the fastest way to solve proportions.</div>
<div class="formula-box">
<div class="formula">a/b = c/d &nbsp;→&nbsp; ad = bc &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (cross-multiply)</div>
<div class="formula-sub">Works whenever two fractions are equal to each other</div>
</div>
<div class="grid2">
<div class="mini"><div class="mini-t">Direct variation</div><div class="mini-b">y = kx — as x increases, y increases proportionally. k is the constant of variation.</div><div class="mini-ex">If y varies directly with x and y=12 when x=4:<br>k = 12/4 = 3 → y = 3x<br>When x=7: y=21</div></div>
<div class="mini"><div class="mini-t">Inverse variation</div><div class="mini-b">y = k/x — as x increases, y decreases. The product xy is always constant (= k).</div><div class="mini-ex">If y varies inversely with x and y=6 when x=4:<br>k = 6·4 = 24 → y = 24/x<br>When x=8: y=3</div></div>
</div>
<div class="ex-box"><div class="ex-label">Worked example — part-to-part vs part-to-whole</div>
<div class="fb-work">A mixture has oil and water in ratio 2:5.<br>Total parts = 2+5 = 7<br>Fraction that is oil = 2/7<br>Fraction that is water = 5/7<br>If total = 350 mL → oil = (2/7)·350 = 100 mL</div></div>
</div>
<div class="card"><div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div><div class="tips-grid">
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Part-to-part vs part-to-whole</div><div class="tip-body">A ratio of 3:5 means 3 parts to 5 parts. Total parts = 8. Fraction of whole = 3/8 or 5/8. The SAT often gives a part-to-part ratio and asks for a fraction of the whole — add the parts first.</div></div>
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Scale problems: set up a proportion</div><div class="tip-body">For unit conversions, maps, or scaled drawings, always set up a proportion with matching units. If 1 inch = 40 miles, then 3.5 inches = x miles → 1/40 = 3.5/x → x = 140 miles.</div></div>
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Direct vs inverse: read the problem</div><div class="tip-body">"Varies directly" → y = kx → as x doubles, y doubles. "Varies inversely" → y = k/x → as x doubles, y halves. Find k from the given pair, then use it to find the unknown.</div></div>
<div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Check units throughout</div><div class="tip-body">In proportion problems, make sure corresponding quantities have the same units on each side. Miles/hour on the left must match miles/hour on the right — not miles on one side and hours on the other.</div></div>
