<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 3 · Lesson 3.18</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Percentages</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master all percentage calculations — percent of a number, percent change, reverse percentages, and successive percent changes — one of the most reliable point sources on the SAT.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>12 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">The five percentage problem types</div>
  <div class="formula-box">
    <div class="formula">
      Percent = (Part / Whole) × 100<br>
      Part = Whole × (Percent / 100)<br>
      % Change = (New − Old) / Old × 100
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="types-grid">
    <div class="type-card">
      <div class="type-title">Type 1 — Find the percent</div>
      <div class="type-body">What percent of 80 is 20?</div>
      <div class="type-ex">20/80 × 100 = 25%</div>
    </div>
    <div class="type-card">
      <div class="type-title">Type 2 — Find the part</div>
      <div class="type-body">What is 35% of 120?</div>
      <div class="type-ex">120 × 0.35 = 42</div>
    </div>
    <div class="type-card">
      <div class="type-title">Type 3 — Find the whole (reverse %)</div>
      <div class="type-body">18 is 30% of what number?</div>
      <div class="type-ex">18 / 0.30 = 60</div>
    </div>
    <div class="type-card">
      <div class="type-title">Type 4 — Percent change</div>
      <div class="type-body">Price went from $40 to $52. What % increase?</div>
      <div class="type-ex">(52−40)/40 × 100 = 30%</div>
    </div>
    <div class="type-card">
      <div class="type-title">Type 5 — Successive % changes</div>
      <div class="type-body">Two percent changes in sequence — multiply the multipliers, don't add the percentages.</div>
      <div class="type-ex">+20% then −20%: 1.2 × 0.8 = 0.96 → net −4%<br>(NOT 0% as you might expect)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="type-card">
      <div class="type-title">Type 6 — Percent of percent</div>
      <div class="type-body">A store marks up an item 40%, then discounts it 25%. Net effect?</div>
      <div class="type-ex">1.40 × 0.75 = 1.05 → net +5%<br>Multiply the multipliers, read the result.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — reverse percentage</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      After a 15% discount, a jacket costs $85. What was the original price?<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">After 15% off: price = original × (1 − 0.15) = original × 0.85</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">So: 0.85 × original = 85</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Original = 85 / 0.85 = $100</span><br><br>
      Common mistake: adding 15% to $85 gives $97.75 — that's wrong because 15% of the discounted price ≠ 15% of the original.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Use multipliers for percent change</div><div class="tip-body">For any percent change, use a multiplier: +r% → multiply by (1 + r/100). −r% → multiply by (1 − r/100). This works for forward and reverse calculations, and chains easily for successive changes.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Reverse percentage — divide, don't subtract</div><div class="tip-body">If a price after a 20% increase is $120, the original is $120 ÷ 1.20 = $100 — not $120 − $24 = $96. Always divide by the multiplier to reverse a percentage.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Successive changes — multiply, don't add</div><div class="tip-body">Two 10% increases is NOT a 20% increase. It's 1.10 × 1.10 = 1.21, which is a 21% total increase. Never add percentage changes — always multiply their multipliers.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Percent greater/less than traps</div><div class="tip-body">"A is 25% greater than B" → A = 1.25B. "A is 25% less than B" → A = 0.75B. The SAT uses these phrasings carefully — "greater than" means the multiplier is above 1, "less than" means below 1.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="sec-title" style="margin-bottom:.75rem">Practice questions</div>
<div class="q-tabs">
  <button class="q-tab active" onclick="switchQ(0,this)">Question 1</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(1,this)">Question 2</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(2,this)">Question 3</button>
</div>

<div class="q-panel active" id="qp-0">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A store increases a product's price by 20%, then later reduces the new price by 20%.</div>
      <div class="hint">Use multipliers: +20% → ×1.20, then −20% → ×0.80. Multiply them together. The result shows the net multiplier relative to the original price.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 1 · Successive % Changes</div>
      <div class="q-text">What is the <strong>net percent change</strong> from the original price?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-0">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>0% — the price returns to the original</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>+4% — the price is slightly higher</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>−4% — the price is slightly lower</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>−20% — the increases and decreases cancel</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-ok"><strong>Correct! −4%</strong><div class="fb-work">Net multiplier: 1.20 × 0.80 = 0.96<br>0.96 = 1 − 0.04 → net change = −4%<br><br>Example: $100 → ×1.20 → $120 → ×0.80 → $96<br>$96 is 4% less than the original $100. ✓<br><br>The percentages don't cancel because 20% of $120 ≠ 20% of $100.</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Don't add the percentages — multiply the multipliers: 1.20 × 0.80. Try with a concrete number: start with $100, apply each change, and see where you end up.<div class="fb-work">$100 × 1.20 = $120 · $120 × 0.80 = $96 → −4%</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-0" onclick="check(0,'C')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-1">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">After receiving a 12% raise, an employee earns $3,136 per month.</div>
      <div class="hint">After a 12% raise: new salary = original × 1.12. So original = new ÷ 1.12. Divide the new salary by the multiplier to reverse the percentage.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · Reverse Percentage</div>
      <div class="q-text">What was the employee's salary <strong>before</strong> the raise?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>$2,759</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>$2,800</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>$2,950</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>$3,512</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-ok"><strong>Correct! $2,800</strong><div class="fb-work">New = Old × 1.12<br>3,136 = Old × 1.12<br>Old = 3,136 / 1.12 = 2,800<br>Check: $2,800 × 1.12 = $3,136 ✓<br><br>Common error: $3,136 − 12% = $3,136 × 0.88 = $2,760 ✗<br>(That would reverse a 12% decrease, not increase.)</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> To reverse a 12% increase, divide by 1.12 — don't subtract 12% from the new salary. Subtracting 12% undoes a decrease, not an increase.<div class="fb-work">3,136 ÷ 1.12 = $2,800</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-1" onclick="check(1,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-2">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">In a survey, 60% of respondents said they exercise regularly. Of those who exercise regularly, 45% said they exercise more than 5 times per week.</div>
      <div class="hint">This is a "percent of a percent" problem. Find 45% of the 60% who exercise regularly. Multiply: 0.60 × 0.45 = what fraction of all respondents?</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 3 · Percent of Percent</div>
      <div class="q-text">What percent of <strong>all respondents</strong> exercise more than 5 times per week?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-2">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>27%</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>45%</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>105%</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>36%</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-ok"><strong>Correct! 27%</strong><div class="fb-work">60% exercise regularly<br>45% of those exercise 5+ times/week<br>Fraction of ALL: 0.60 × 0.45 = 0.27 = 27% ✓<br><br>Option B (45%) is the percentage among exercisers only — not all respondents.<br>Option D (36%) adds instead of multiplies: 60%+45%−something — wrong approach.</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> 45% is the percentage within the subgroup — not the whole survey. To find what fraction of everyone exercises 5+ times, multiply: 60% of respondents × 45% of those.<div class="fb-work">0.60 × 0.45 = 0.27 = 27%</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-2" onclick="check(2,'A')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

