<div class="lesson-title">Unit Analysis & Conversions</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master dimensional analysis — the systematic method for converting units and solving multi-step rate problems by tracking units like algebraic variables until only the target unit remains.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>11 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Dimensional analysis — treating units as algebra</div>
  <div class="body-text">Every measurement has a number and a unit. In dimensional analysis, you multiply by conversion factors — fractions equal to 1 — that cancel unwanted units and introduce the target unit. Units cancel exactly like variables in algebra.</div>
  <div class="chain-box">
    <div class="chain-title">The conversion chain method</div>
    <div class="chain-text">
      [Given value] × [conversion₁] × [conversion₂] × ... = [target value]
    </div>
    <div class="chain-note">Set up each conversion factor so the unit you want to eliminate is on the bottom, and the unit you want to introduce is on top. Units cancel diagonally — if the same unit appears in a numerator and denominator, cross it out.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — multi-step conversion</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      A car travels at 60 miles per hour. Convert this speed to feet per second.<br>
      (Use: 1 mile = 5,280 feet; 1 hour = 3,600 seconds)<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">60 miles/hour × (5,280 feet / 1 mile) × (1 hour / 3,600 seconds)</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">= 60 × 5,280 / 3,600 feet/second</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">= 316,800 / 3,600 = 88 feet/second</span><br><br>
      Notice: "miles" cancelled (it appeared in numerator and denominator), "hours" cancelled — only "feet/second" remains.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — rate × rate</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      A factory produces 240 widgets per hour. Each widget requires 3 parts. How many parts are used in 5 hours?<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">5 hours × (240 widgets/hour) × (3 parts/widget)</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">= 5 × 240 × 3 = 3,600 parts</span><br><br>
      "Hours" and "widgets" both cancel — only "parts" remains. ✓
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Write units in every step</div><div class="tip-body">Never do unit conversion mentally. Write the full fraction with units at every step. Units cancel just like algebraic variables — if the same unit is on top and bottom, cross it out. This prevents the most common conversion errors.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">The target unit must be the only one left</div><div class="tip-body">After cancelling all units in your chain, only the target unit should remain. If you still have unwanted units, you need another conversion factor. If you're missing the target unit, you set up a fraction upside down.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Rate × rate chains are powerful</div><div class="tip-body">For problems with multiple rates (widgets/hour and parts/widget), multiply them as a chain. The middle unit (widgets) cancels, leaving the final unit (parts/hour). This works for any chain of compatible rates.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Identify the target unit first</div><div class="tip-body">Before setting up any conversion, write down the unit you need at the end. Then build your chain backwards — each conversion factor introduces what the next step needs, until you have the target.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

