<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 3 · Lesson 3.20</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Statistics & Data Interpretation</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master mean, median, mode, range, and standard deviation — and learn how outliers and data changes affect each measure, the most tested aspect of statistics on the SAT.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">The five key measures</div>
  <div class="stats-grid">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-title">Mean (average)</div>
      <div class="stat-def">Sum of all values ÷ number of values. Affected by every data point — especially sensitive to outliers.</div>
      <div class="stat-ex">Data: 2, 4, 6, 8, 10<br>Mean = 30/5 = 6</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-title">Median</div>
      <div class="stat-def">The middle value when data is ordered. For even-numbered datasets, average the two middle values. Resistant to outliers.</div>
      <div class="stat-ex">Data: 2, 4, 6, 8, 10 → median = 6<br>Data: 2, 4, 6, 8 → median = (4+6)/2 = 5</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-title">Mode</div>
      <div class="stat-def">The value that appears most often. A dataset can have no mode, one mode, or multiple modes.</div>
      <div class="stat-ex">Data: 3, 5, 5, 7, 9 → mode = 5<br>Data: 1, 2, 3, 4 → no mode</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-title">Range</div>
      <div class="stat-def">Maximum − Minimum. Measures the spread of the entire dataset. Extremely sensitive to outliers.</div>
      <div class="stat-ex">Data: 2, 4, 6, 8, 10<br>Range = 10 − 2 = 8</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="stat-card" style="margin-top:10px;">
    <div class="stat-title">Standard deviation</div>
    <div class="stat-def">Measures how spread out the data is around the mean. High SD = data is spread widely. Low SD = data clusters near the mean. You don't need to calculate it on the SAT — just interpret it: larger SD means more spread, smaller SD means more concentrated.</div>
    <div class="stat-ex">Dataset A: 10, 10, 10, 10 → SD = 0 (no spread)<br>Dataset B: 1, 5, 10, 15, 19 → SD is large (wide spread)</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">How changes to data affect each measure</div>
  <div class="body-text">The SAT's most common statistics question: what happens to mean, median, and range when you add, remove, or change a data value?</div>
  <div class="effect-grid">
    <div class="effect-card" style="background:#EDE9FE;">
      <div class="effect-title" style="color:#4C1D95;">Add/remove a value equal to mean</div>
      <div class="effect-body">Mean stays the same. Median may change. Range unchanged (if not extreme).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="effect-card" style="background:#FCEBEB;">
      <div class="effect-title" style="color:#A32D2D;">Add an outlier (very high or low)</div>
      <div class="effect-body">Mean shifts toward outlier. Median barely changes. Range increases significantly.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="effect-card" style="background:#EAF3DE;">
      <div class="effect-title" style="color:#27500A;">Add a constant k to every value</div>
      <div class="effect-body">Mean, median, mode all increase by k. Range and SD stay the same.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="effect-card" style="background:#FEF3C7;">
      <div class="effect-title" style="color:#92400E;">Multiply every value by k</div>
      <div class="effect-body">Mean, median, mode all multiply by k. Range and SD also multiply by k.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="effect-card" style="background:#F5F3FF;">
      <div class="effect-title" style="color:#4C1D95;">Remove an outlier</div>
      <div class="effect-body">Mean moves away from the outlier. Median may change slightly. Range decreases.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="effect-card" style="background:#f9fafb;">
      <div class="effect-title">Replace a value with the mean</div>
      <div class="effect-body">Mean stays the same. SD decreases (less spread). Range may decrease.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Mean is the SAT's favorite statistic</div><div class="tip-body">Most statistics questions involve the mean. Remember: mean = sum ÷ count. To find a missing value when the mean is given: total sum = mean × count. Then subtract the known values to find the missing one.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Outliers move mean, not median</div><div class="tip-body">Adding or removing an extreme value changes the mean significantly but barely moves the median. If a question asks which measure is "most affected" by an outlier — the answer is always mean (and range).</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Median requires ordering the data</div><div class="tip-body">Always sort the data before finding the median. For n values: if n is odd, median = value at position (n+1)/2. If n is even, median = average of values at positions n/2 and n/2 + 1.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">SD interpretation without calculation</div><div class="tip-body">You never need to calculate SD on the SAT. Just know: higher SD = more spread from the mean. If two datasets have the same mean but different SDs, the one with lower SD has values clustered more tightly.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="sec-title" style="margin-bottom:.75rem">Practice questions</div>
<div class="q-tabs">
  <button class="q-tab active" onclick="switchQ(0,this)">Question 1</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(1,this)">Question 2</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(2,this)">Question 3</button>
</div>

<div class="q-panel active" id="qp-0">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">The scores of 5 students on a test are:</div>
      <div class="data-row">
        <span class="data-val">72</span><span class="data-val">85</span><span class="data-val">90</span><span class="data-val">68</span><span class="data-val">x</span>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-text">The mean score is 82.</div>
      <div class="hint">Mean = sum ÷ count. So sum = mean × count = 82 × 5 = 410. Add up the four known values and subtract from 410 to find x.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 1 · Finding a Missing Value</div>
      <div class="q-text">What is the value of <strong>x</strong>?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-0">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>95</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>82</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>90</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>75</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-ok"><strong>Correct! x = 95</strong><div class="fb-work">Total sum = 82 × 5 = 410<br>Known sum: 72+85+90+68 = 315<br>x = 410 − 315 = 95 ✓<br>Check: (72+85+90+68+95)/5 = 410/5 = 82 ✓</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Total sum = mean × count = 82 × 5 = 410. Find the sum of the four known values, then subtract.<div class="fb-work">72+85+90+68 = 315 · x = 410−315 = 95</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-0" onclick="check(0,'A')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-1">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A dataset has 7 values:</div>
      <div class="data-row">
        <span class="data-val">4</span><span class="data-val">7</span><span class="data-val">9</span><span class="data-val">12</span><span class="data-val">15</span><span class="data-val">18</span><span class="data-val">100</span>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-text" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">The value 100 is a data entry error. It is removed from the dataset.</div>
      <div class="hint">Calculate the mean and median both before and after removing 100. Remember to re-sort and find the new middle value for the median of 6 values.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · Effect of Removing an Outlier</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which statement correctly describes the effect of removing 100?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>Both mean and median decrease significantly.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>Mean decreases significantly; median changes only slightly.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>Mean stays the same; median decreases significantly.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>Both mean and median stay approximately the same.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong><div class="fb-work">With 100: mean=(4+7+9+12+15+18+100)/7=165/7≈23.6 · median=12<br>Without 100: mean=(4+7+9+12+15+18)/6=65/6≈10.8 · median=(9+12)/2=10.5<br><br>Mean: 23.6→10.8 = large decrease ✓<br>Median: 12→10.5 = small change ✓<br>Outliers strongly affect mean but barely affect median.</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Calculate mean and median with and without 100. The outlier (100) pulls the mean far above most values. The median (middle value) is barely affected by extreme values at the ends.<div class="fb-work">Mean drops from ≈23.6 to ≈10.8 · Median changes from 12 to 10.5</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-1" onclick="check(1,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-2">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">Two classes took the same exam. Class A has a mean of 74 and standard deviation of 12. Class B has a mean of 74 and standard deviation of 4.</div>
      <div class="hint">Both classes have the same mean — so the average performance is identical. The standard deviation tells you about spread. Lower SD = scores cluster tightly around the mean. Higher SD = scores are more spread out.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 3 · Interpreting Standard Deviation</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which statement best compares the two classes?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-2">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>Class A performed better on average than Class B.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>Class B's scores are more consistent — most students scored closer to 74.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>Class A's scores are more consistent — most students scored closer to 74.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>Class B had more students scoring above 74 than Class A.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> Both classes have the same mean (74), so neither performed better on average — A is wrong. SD measures spread: Class B has SD = 4, meaning scores cluster tightly around 74. Class A has SD = 12, meaning scores are spread widely — more students scored far from 74. Option B correctly identifies Class B as more consistent. Option D cannot be concluded from SD alone.</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Both classes have the same mean — so average performance is identical. The difference is in standard deviation. Lower SD means scores are clustered closer to the mean (more consistent). Which class has the lower SD?<div class="fb-work">Class B: SD=4 → more consistent (tighter clustering around 74)</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-2" onclick="check(2,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

