<div class="lesson-title">Scatterplots & Data Analysis</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master reading and interpreting scatterplots, lines of best fit, and two-variable data — and learn the critical distinction between correlation and causation that the SAT tests every year.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>12 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Scatterplot concepts</div>
  <div class="concepts-grid">
    <div class="concept-card">
      <div class="concept-title">Positive association</div>
      <div class="concept-body">As x increases, y tends to increase. Points slope upward from left to right. Line of best fit has positive slope.</div>
      <div class="concept-ex">Study time vs. test score<br>Height vs. weight</div>
    </div>
    <div class="concept-card">
      <div class="concept-title">Negative association</div>
      <div class="concept-body">As x increases, y tends to decrease. Points slope downward from left to right. Line of best fit has negative slope.</div>
      <div class="concept-ex">Hours of TV vs. grades<br>Distance from city vs. property value</div>
    </div>
    <div class="concept-card">
      <div class="concept-title">Line of best fit</div>
      <div class="concept-body">A line drawn through a scatterplot that minimizes the overall distance to all data points. Used to make predictions and estimate values not in the dataset.</div>
      <div class="concept-ex">Read it like any linear equation: slope = rate of change, y-intercept = predicted y when x = 0.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="concept-card">
      <div class="concept-title">Interpolation vs. extrapolation</div>
      <div class="concept-body">Interpolation = predicting within the range of the data (reliable). Extrapolation = predicting outside the data range (less reliable — the SAT may ask about this).</div>
      <div class="concept-ex">Data from x=10 to x=50. Predicting at x=30 = interpolation. Predicting at x=100 = extrapolation.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="concept-card">
      <div class="concept-title">Strength of association</div>
      <div class="concept-body">Strong association: points cluster closely around the line. Weak association: points are scattered far from the line. No association: no clear pattern.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="concept-card">
      <div class="concept-title">Outliers in scatterplots</div>
      <div class="concept-body">A point far from the line of best fit. Outliers don't necessarily invalidate the trend — they may represent unusual cases worth investigating separately.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="warn-box">
    <div class="warn-label">Correlation ≠ Causation — the SAT's most tested statistical concept</div>
    <div class="warn-text">A scatterplot showing a strong association between two variables does NOT mean one causes the other. Both variables might be caused by a third factor (confounding variable), or the association might be coincidental. The SAT will always present incorrect answer choices that claim causation from correlation data.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Read the line of best fit as an equation</div><div class="tip-body">When given a line of best fit, identify the slope and y-intercept. The slope tells you the predicted change in y per unit increase in x. Use the equation to make predictions at specific x-values.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Correlation ≠ causation — always</div><div class="tip-body">If an answer choice says "X causes Y" based on a scatterplot, it's wrong. Scatterplots show association, not causation. The SAT always includes "X causes Y" as a trap answer.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Residuals = actual − predicted</div><div class="tip-body">A residual is the difference between an actual data point and the value predicted by the line of best fit. Positive residual = above the line. Negative residual = below the line.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Two-way tables — marginal vs. conditional</div><div class="tip-body">In two-way tables, "marginal" totals are the row/column sums. "Conditional" probability uses a specific row or column as the denominator. Read the question carefully to know which total to use as the base.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="sec-title" style="margin-bottom:.75rem">Practice questions</div>
<div class="q-tabs">
  <button class="q-tab active" onclick="switchQ(0,this)">Question 1</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(1,this)">Question 2</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(2,this)">Question 3</button>
</div>

<div class="q-panel active" id="qp-0">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A scatterplot shows the relationship between hours spent studying (x) and exam score (y). The line of best fit has the equation:</div>
      <span class="math-eq">y = 4.5x + 42</span>
      <div class="hint">The slope 4.5 means for each additional hour of study, the predicted score increases by 4.5 points. The y-intercept 42 is the predicted score with 0 hours of study.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 1 · Interpreting Line of Best Fit</div>
      <div class="q-text">What does the <strong>slope</strong> of this line of best fit represent?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-0">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>The predicted exam score for a student who studies 0 hours</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>The predicted increase in exam score for each additional hour of study</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>The total number of hours studied by all students</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>The maximum possible exam score</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> The slope (4.5) represents the rate of change — for each additional hour of study (x increases by 1), the predicted score (y) increases by 4.5 points. Option A describes the y-intercept (42), not the slope.</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> In y = mx + b, the slope m tells you how much y changes per unit increase in x. Here, for every 1 additional hour studied, what happens to the predicted score?<div class="fb-work">slope = 4.5 → score increases 4.5 points per hour</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-0" onclick="check(0,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-1">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A researcher finds a strong positive association between the number of fire trucks sent to a fire and the total damage caused by the fire.</div>
      <div class="hint">This is a correlation vs. causation question. A strong association does NOT mean one variable causes the other. Ask: is there a third variable that explains both?</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · Correlation vs. Causation</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which conclusion is <strong>best supported</strong> by this finding?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>Sending more fire trucks causes more damage to the fire.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>The number of fire trucks and damage are positively associated, likely because larger fires require both more trucks and cause more damage.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>Cities should send fewer fire trucks to reduce fire damage.</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>Fire damage causes cities to buy more fire trucks.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> A positive association between trucks and damage doesn't mean trucks cause damage. The confounding variable is fire size — larger fires require more trucks AND cause more damage. Both variables are driven by a third factor (fire size). Options A and C wrongly imply causation and would lead to absurd policy conclusions. Option D reverses the logic entirely.</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Correlation does NOT imply causation. Think about what else might explain why bigger fires have both more trucks and more damage. Is there a third variable driving both?<div class="fb-work">Fire size → more trucks AND more damage. Trucks don't cause damage.</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-1" onclick="check(1,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="q-panel" id="qp-2">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">The line of best fit for a scatterplot has equation y = 2x + 5. One data point in the scatterplot is (6, 20).</div>
      <div class="hint">The residual = actual y − predicted y. First find the predicted y from the line of best fit at x = 6. Then subtract from the actual y value of 20.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 3 · Residuals</div>
      <div class="q-text">What is the <strong>residual</strong> for the point (6, 20)?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-2">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>−3</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>3</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>7</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>−7</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-ok"><strong>Correct! Residual = 3</strong><div class="fb-work">Predicted y at x=6: y = 2(6)+5 = 17<br>Actual y = 20<br>Residual = actual − predicted = 20 − 17 = 3 ✓<br><br>Positive residual → point is ABOVE the line of best fit.<br>The actual score (20) is 3 higher than the model predicts (17).</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Residual = actual y − predicted y. Find the predicted value using the equation: y = 2(6) + 5 = 17. Then subtract from the actual value of 20.<div class="fb-work">20 − 17 = 3 (point is above the line)</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-2" onclick="check(2,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

