<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 3 · Lesson 3.22</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Probability</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master basic probability, conditional probability, and expected value — and learn to read two-way tables to calculate probabilities quickly and accurately.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>12 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Probability fundamentals</div>
  <div class="formula-box">
    <div class="formula">
      P(event) = favorable outcomes / total outcomes<br>
      P(A and B) = P(A) × P(B) &nbsp; [if independent]<br>
      P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) − P(A and B)<br>
      P(A | B) = P(A and B) / P(B) &nbsp; [conditional]
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="rules-grid">
    <div class="rule-card">
      <div class="rule-title">Basic probability</div>
      <div class="rule-body">Always between 0 and 1. P = 0 means impossible. P = 1 means certain. All probabilities in a sample space sum to 1.</div>
      <div class="rule-ex">P(rolling a 3 on a die) = 1/6<br>P(not rolling 3) = 1 − 1/6 = 5/6</div>
    </div>
    <div class="rule-card">
      <div class="rule-title">Independent events</div>
      <div class="rule-body">Events are independent if one doesn't affect the other. Multiply probabilities: P(A and B) = P(A) × P(B).</div>
      <div class="rule-ex">P(heads twice) = 1/2 × 1/2 = 1/4<br>P(red then blue) = P(red) × P(blue)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="rule-card">
      <div class="rule-title">Conditional probability P(A|B)</div>
      <div class="rule-body">"Probability of A given B" — restricts the sample space to only outcomes where B occurred. The denominator is the total for condition B.</div>
      <div class="rule-ex">In a table: P(senior | female)<br>= # senior females / # total females</div>
    </div>
    <div class="rule-card">
      <div class="rule-title">Complementary events</div>
      <div class="rule-body">P(not A) = 1 − P(A). Often faster than calculating P(A) directly, especially for "at least one" problems.</div>
      <div class="rule-ex">P(at least one head in 3 flips)<br>= 1 − P(all tails)<br>= 1 − (1/2)³ = 7/8</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Two-way tables — the SAT's favorite probability format</div>
  <div class="body-text">Two-way tables organize data by two categories. Most SAT probability questions can be solved directly by reading the right cells from the table.</div>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="two-way">
      <tr><th></th><th>Prefers math</th><th>Prefers English</th><th>Total</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Grade 11</strong></td><td>45</td><td>30</td><td class="total">75</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Grade 12</strong></td><td>35</td><td>40</td><td class="total">75</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="total">Total</td><td class="total">80</td><td class="total">70</td><td class="total">150</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Reading the table — three types of probability</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      <strong>Basic:</strong> P(prefers math) = 80/150 = 8/15<br>
      <strong>Conditional:</strong> P(prefers math | Grade 11) = 45/75 = 3/5 &nbsp; ← use Grade 11 total (75) as denominator<br>
      <strong>Joint:</strong> P(Grade 12 AND prefers English) = 40/150 = 4/15
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Conditional probability — restrict the denominator</div><div class="tip-body">P(A | B) uses the B total as denominator, not the overall total. "Given that the student is female" → use the female total. This is the most common probability error on the SAT.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Use complementary probability for "at least one"</div><div class="tip-body">P(at least one A) = 1 − P(no A at all). This is almost always faster than calculating P(exactly one) + P(exactly two) + ... separately.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Independent events: check if P(A|B) = P(A)</div><div class="tip-body">Two events are independent if knowing B occurred doesn't change the probability of A. Formally: P(A|B) = P(A). The SAT asks this directly in some questions.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Read the question — marginal vs. conditional</div><div class="tip-body">"What fraction of all students" → use grand total. "What fraction of Grade 11 students" → use Grade 11 total. The key word in the question tells you which total is the denominator.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

