<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 3 · Lesson 3.1</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Linear Equations — One Variable</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master solving equations with a single unknown — the foundation of all SAT algebra. Learn the step-by-step method and how to handle the three special cases.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>12 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">What is a linear equation in one variable?</div>
  <div class="body-text">A linear equation in one variable contains a single unknown (usually x) raised to the first power. The goal is always the same: <strong>isolate x</strong> on one side of the equation by performing the same operations on both sides.</div>
  <div class="formula-box">
    <div class="formula">ax + b = c</div>
    <div class="formula-sub">where a, b, and c are constants and x is the unknown. Solution: x = (c − b) / a</div>
  </div>
  <div class="steps-list">
    <div class="step-item">
      <div class="step-num">1</div>
      <div class="step-body"><strong>Distribute and simplify each side.</strong> Expand any parentheses. Combine like terms on each side separately before moving anything across the equals sign.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="step-item">
      <div class="step-num">2</div>
      <div class="step-body"><strong>Move variable terms to one side.</strong> Add or subtract terms containing x so all x-terms are on the left. Add or subtract constants so all numbers are on the right.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="step-item">
      <div class="step-num">3</div>
      <div class="step-body"><strong>Divide by the coefficient of x.</strong> Whatever number is multiplied by x — divide both sides by it. This isolates x and gives the solution.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="step-item">
      <div class="step-num">4</div>
      <div class="step-body"><strong>Check by substituting back.</strong> Plug your answer into the original equation and verify both sides are equal. This catches arithmetic errors in under 10 seconds.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      Solve: <strong>3(2x − 4) + 5 = 2x + 9</strong><br><br>
      Step 1 — Distribute: &nbsp; 6x − 12 + 5 = 2x + 9 &nbsp;→&nbsp; 6x − 7 = 2x + 9<br>
      Step 2 — Move x-terms left: &nbsp; 6x − 2x − 7 = 9 &nbsp;→&nbsp; 4x − 7 = 9<br>
      Step 3 — Move constants right: &nbsp; 4x = 16<br>
      Step 4 — Divide: &nbsp; x = 4<br>
      Check: 3(2·4 − 4) + 5 = 3(4) + 5 = 17 &nbsp;|&nbsp; 2(4) + 9 = 17 ✓
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Three special cases</div>
  <div class="two-col">
    <div class="mini-card">
      <div class="mini-title" style="color:#3B6D11;">One solution (normal)</div>
      <div class="mini-body">After solving, x equals a specific number. The equation is satisfied by exactly one value.</div>
      <div class="mini-ex">2x + 3 = 11 → x = 4 ✓</div>
    </div>
    <div class="mini-card">
      <div class="mini-title" style="color:#A32D2D;">No solution</div>
      <div class="mini-body">After simplifying, you get a false statement like 5 = 8. No value of x makes this true.</div>
      <div class="mini-ex">2x + 5 = 2x + 8 → 5 = 8 (impossible)</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mini-card" style="margin-top:10px;">
    <div class="mini-title" style="color:#7C3AED;">Infinitely many solutions</div>
    <div class="mini-body">After simplifying, you get a true statement like 0 = 0 or 5 = 5. Every value of x satisfies the equation.</div>
    <div class="mini-ex">2(x + 3) = 2x + 6 → 6 = 6 (always true — all real numbers are solutions)</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Always distribute before moving terms</div><div class="tip-body">Don't move terms across the equals sign until you've fully expanded parentheses on each side. Moving before distributing causes the most common errors.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Watch for "no solution" traps</div><div class="tip-body">The SAT often writes equations that look solvable but produce a contradiction. If your x-terms cancel and leave a false statement — the answer is "no solution," not 0.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Fractions: multiply both sides by LCD first</div><div class="tip-body">If the equation has fractions, multiply every term by the least common denominator to clear them before solving. This prevents arithmetic errors.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Always verify with a check</div><div class="tip-body">On the SAT, substituting your answer back into the original equation takes 15 seconds and catches most errors. Always do it when time allows.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

