<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 3 · Lesson 3.2</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Linear Equations — Two Variables</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master the slope-intercept and standard forms of linear equations, learn what slope and y-intercept mean in context, and practice reading and writing linear equations from graphs and tables.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>14 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">The two key forms of a linear equation</div>
  <div class="body-text">A linear equation in two variables describes a straight line — every point (x, y) that satisfies the equation lies on that line. The SAT uses two main forms.</div>
  <div class="forms-grid">
    <div class="form-card">
      <div class="form-title">Slope-intercept form</div>
      <div class="form-eq">y = mx + b</div>
      <div class="form-body"><strong>m</strong> = slope (rate of change) · <strong>b</strong> = y-intercept (value of y when x = 0). Best for reading slope and intercept directly, graphing, and word problems involving rates.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="form-card">
      <div class="form-title">Standard form</div>
      <div class="form-eq">Ax + By = C</div>
      <div class="form-body"><strong>A, B, C</strong> are integers. Best for systems of equations and finding intercepts: set x = 0 for y-intercept, set y = 0 for x-intercept.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="formula-box">
    <div class="formula">slope m = (y₂ − y₁) / (x₂ − x₁) = rise / run</div>
    <div class="formula-sub">Positive slope → line rises left to right · Negative slope → line falls left to right · Zero slope → horizontal line · Undefined slope → vertical line</div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — writing an equation from two points</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      Find the equation of the line through (2, 5) and (6, 13).<br><br>
      <span class="work">Step 1: slope = (13 − 5) / (6 − 2) = 8 / 4 = 2</span><br>
      <span class="work">Step 2: use y = mx + b → 5 = 2(2) + b → b = 1</span><br>
      <span class="work">Equation: y = 2x + 1</span><br><br>
      Check with (6, 13): y = 2(6) + 1 = 13 ✓
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">What slope and intercept mean in real-world contexts</div>
  <div class="body-text">The SAT frequently asks you to interpret the slope and y-intercept of a linear model — not just calculate them. The key is connecting the math to the story.</div>
  <div class="two-col">
    <div class="mini-card">
      <div class="mini-title">Slope = rate of change</div>
      <div class="mini-body">The slope tells you how much y changes for each one-unit increase in x. In a word problem, ask: what are the units of the slope?</div>
      <div class="mini-ex">y = 0.15x + 20 (cost of phone plan)<br>Slope 0.15 = $0.15 per minute of usage<br>Each extra minute costs $0.15 more.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="mini-card">
      <div class="mini-title">y-intercept = starting value</div>
      <div class="mini-body">The y-intercept is the value of y when x = 0 — the baseline, initial amount, or fixed cost before any change occurs.</div>
      <div class="mini-ex">y = 0.15x + 20 (cost of phone plan)<br>y-intercept 20 = $20 flat monthly fee<br>The cost before any minutes are used.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Convert to slope-intercept for reading</div><div class="tip-body">If an equation is given in standard form (Ax + By = C), solve for y to get slope-intercept form. This makes slope and y-intercept immediately visible without extra calculation.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Use two points to find slope first</div><div class="tip-body">When given a table or graph, always find slope first using two clear points. Then substitute one point into y = mx + b to find b. Never try to find b without finding m first.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Parallel lines have equal slopes</div><div class="tip-body">Two lines are parallel if and only if their slopes are equal (and they have different y-intercepts). Perpendicular lines have slopes that are negative reciprocals of each other: m₁ × m₂ = −1.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">x-intercept: set y = 0</div><div class="tip-body">The x-intercept is where the line crosses the x-axis — set y = 0 and solve for x. The y-intercept is where it crosses the y-axis — set x = 0 and solve for y.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

