<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 3 · Lesson 3.3</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Systems of Linear Equations</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master two methods for solving systems of two equations — substitution and elimination — and learn to identify when a system has one solution, no solution, or infinitely many solutions.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>14 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Two methods — choose the faster one</div>
  <div class="body-text">A system of two linear equations has two unknowns. To solve it, you must find the values of both variables that satisfy both equations simultaneously. The SAT rewards you for choosing the most efficient method.</div>
  <div class="method-grid">
    <div class="method-card" style="background:#F5F3FF;">
      <div class="method-title" style="color:#4C1D95;">Substitution — best when one variable is already isolated</div>
      <div class="method-steps">
        1. Solve one equation for one variable<br>
        2. Substitute that expression into the other equation<br>
        3. Solve for the remaining variable<br>
        4. Back-substitute to find the first variable<br><br>
        <em>Best for: y = ... or x = ... equations</em>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="method-card" style="background:#EDE9FE;">
      <div class="method-title" style="color:#4C1D95;">Elimination — best when coefficients are easy to match</div>
      <div class="method-steps">
        1. Multiply one or both equations so a variable has equal (or opposite) coefficients<br>
        2. Add or subtract the equations to eliminate that variable<br>
        3. Solve for the remaining variable<br>
        4. Substitute back to find the other variable<br><br>
        <em>Best for: Ax + By = C form</em>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — elimination</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      Solve: <strong>3x + 2y = 16</strong> and <strong>x − 2y = 0</strong><br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Add equations: (3x + 2y) + (x − 2y) = 16 + 0</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">4x = 16 → x = 4</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Substitute: 4 − 2y = 0 → y = 2</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Solution: (4, 2)</span><br>
      Check in eq 1: 3(4) + 2(2) = 16 ✓ &nbsp; Check in eq 2: 4 − 2(2) = 0 ✓
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Three possible outcomes — what they mean geometrically</div>
  <div class="solutions-grid">
    <div class="sol-card" style="background:#EAF3DE;">
      <div class="sol-title" style="color:#27500A;">One solution</div>
      <div class="sol-cond" style="color:#3B6D11;">Lines intersect at exactly one point. Different slopes.</div>
      <div class="sol-ex">y = 2x + 1<br>y = −x + 4<br>→ solve: (1, 3)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="sol-card" style="background:#FCEBEB;">
      <div class="sol-title" style="color:#501313;">No solution</div>
      <div class="sol-cond" style="color:#A32D2D;">Lines are parallel. Same slope, different y-intercepts. Variables cancel leaving a false statement.</div>
      <div class="sol-ex">y = 2x + 1<br>y = 2x + 5<br>→ 0 = 4 (false)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="sol-card" style="background:#EDE9FE;">
      <div class="sol-title" style="color:#4C1D95;">Infinite solutions</div>
      <div class="sol-cond" style="color:#7C3AED;">Lines are identical. Same slope and same y-intercept. Variables cancel leaving a true statement.</div>
      <div class="sol-ex">y = 2x + 1<br>2y = 4x + 2<br>→ 0 = 0 (always true)</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Look for the easier variable to eliminate first</div><div class="tip-body">If the coefficients of one variable are already equal or opposite in the two equations, use elimination immediately — no multiplication needed. This saves 30–60 seconds per problem.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">The SAT often asks for x + y, not x or y alone</div><div class="tip-body">Many SAT systems questions ask for a combination like x + y or 2x − y. After eliminating one variable, check if you can get the answer directly without finding both variables separately.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">No solution: same slope, different intercept</div><div class="tip-body">For "no solution" questions, set the equations in slope-intercept form. If slopes are equal but y-intercepts differ, the system has no solution. The SAT frequently tests this condition.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Always check both equations</div><div class="tip-body">After solving, substitute your (x, y) values into both original equations. If both are satisfied, you're done. If not, you made an arithmetic error somewhere — find and fix it.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

