<div class="lesson-title">Inequalities</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Learn to solve linear inequalities, graph solution sets on a number line, and apply the one critical rule that catches most students off guard: what happens when you multiply or divide by a negative number.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>12 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Inequality symbols and what they mean</div>
  <div class="symbol-grid">
    <div class="sym-card">
      <div class="sym-char">&lt;</div>
      <div class="sym-name">Less than</div>
      <div class="sym-ex">x &lt; 5 (open circle at 5, arrow left)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="sym-card">
      <div class="sym-char">&gt;</div>
      <div class="sym-name">Greater than</div>
      <div class="sym-ex">x &gt; 3 (open circle at 3, arrow right)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="sym-card">
      <div class="sym-char">≤</div>
      <div class="sym-name">Less than or equal</div>
      <div class="sym-ex">x ≤ 5 (closed circle at 5, arrow left)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="sym-card">
      <div class="sym-char">≥</div>
      <div class="sym-name">Greater than or equal</div>
      <div class="sym-ex">x ≥ 3 (closed circle at 3, arrow right)</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="body-text" style="margin-top:1rem;">Solving an inequality works exactly like solving an equation — with <strong>one critical exception</strong>.</div>
  <div class="rule-list">
    <div class="rule-item">
      <div class="rule-icon">✓</div>
      <div class="rule-body">
        <strong>Add or subtract the same value from both sides</strong> — inequality sign stays the same.
        <div class="rule-ex">x + 7 &gt; 12 → x &gt; 5 ✓</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="rule-item">
      <div class="rule-icon">✓</div>
      <div class="rule-body">
        <strong>Multiply or divide both sides by a positive number</strong> — inequality sign stays the same.
        <div class="rule-ex">3x ≤ 15 → x ≤ 5 ✓</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="rule-item" style="border: 1.5px solid #FCA5A5;">
      <div class="rule-icon">⚠️</div>
      <div class="rule-body">
        <strong>Multiply or divide both sides by a NEGATIVE number</strong> — FLIP the inequality sign.
        <div class="rule-ex">−2x &lt; 8 → x &gt; −4 (sign flipped!) ✓</div>
        <div class="rule-ex">−3x ≥ 12 → x ≤ −4 (sign flipped!) ✓</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="critical-box">
    <div class="critical-label">Why the sign flips — the intuition</div>
    <div class="critical-text">Think of the number line: 2 &lt; 5 is true. Multiply both sides by −1: −2 and −5. Now −2 is to the right of −5, so −2 &gt; −5. Multiplying by a negative reverses the order of every pair of numbers on the number line. The inequality sign must flip to stay true.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      Solve: <strong>−3(x − 4) + 2 ≥ 14</strong><br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">−3x + 12 + 2 ≥ 14</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">−3x + 14 ≥ 14</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">−3x ≥ 0</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">x ≤ 0 &nbsp;(divide by −3: flip the sign!)</span><br><br>
      Solution set: all x ≤ 0 &nbsp;|&nbsp; Number line: closed circle at 0, arrow pointing left.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Mark negative divisions immediately</div><div class="tip-body">As soon as you see you need to divide by a negative number, circle the inequality sign as a reminder to flip it. This one habit eliminates the most common inequality error.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Compound inequalities: solve all three parts</div><div class="tip-body">For compound inequalities like −3 &lt; 2x + 1 ≤ 9, perform operations on all three parts simultaneously. Whatever you do to the middle, do to both ends.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Test a value in the solution set</div><div class="tip-body">After solving, pick a value that should be in your solution set and substitute it into the original inequality. If it satisfies the inequality, your solution is likely correct.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Real-world inequalities: read "at least" and "at most"</div><div class="tip-body">"At least" = ≥ (greater than or equal). "At most" = ≤ (less than or equal). "More than" = &gt; (strict). "Fewer than" = &lt; (strict). These translations appear on every SAT.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

