<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 3 · Lesson 3.5</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Linear Inequalities & Systems</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Learn to graph linear inequalities in two variables, identify solution regions, and solve systems of inequalities — including the word problems where two constraints must both be satisfied simultaneously.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Graphing a linear inequality in two variables</div>
  <div class="body-text">An inequality like <strong>y &gt; 2x − 1</strong> defines a region of the coordinate plane — all points (x, y) where the inequality holds. Graphing it involves two steps: draw the boundary line, then shade the correct side.</div>
  <div class="steps-list">
    <div class="step-item">
      <div class="step-num">1</div>
      <div class="step-body">
        <strong>Draw the boundary line</strong> by replacing the inequality with an equals sign (y = 2x − 1). Use a <em>dashed</em> line for strict inequalities (&lt; or &gt;) and a <em>solid</em> line for ≤ or ≥.
        <div class="step-ex">Dashed = not included · Solid = included (on the boundary)</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="step-item">
      <div class="step-num">2</div>
      <div class="step-body">
        <strong>Pick a test point</strong> not on the line — (0, 0) works when the line doesn't pass through the origin. Substitute into the inequality.
        <div class="step-ex">y &gt; 2x − 1 : test (0,0) → 0 &gt; −1 ✓ → shade the side containing (0, 0)</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="step-item">
      <div class="step-num">3</div>
      <div class="step-body">
        <strong>Shade the correct half-plane.</strong> If the test point satisfies the inequality, shade the side containing it. If not, shade the opposite side.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="region-grid">
    <div class="region-card">
      <div class="region-title">y &gt; mx + b (above the line)</div>
      <div class="region-body">Shade above the dashed boundary line. All points above have a larger y-value than the line at that x.</div>
      <div class="region-ex">y &gt; 2x − 1: shade above the dashed line y = 2x − 1</div>
    </div>
    <div class="region-card">
      <div class="region-title">y &lt; mx + b (below the line)</div>
      <div class="region-body">Shade below the dashed boundary line. All points below have a smaller y-value than the line at that x.</div>
      <div class="region-ex">y &lt; 2x − 1: shade below the dashed line y = 2x − 1</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Systems of inequalities — the overlapping region</div>
  <div class="body-text">A system of inequalities requires finding all points that satisfy <strong>all</strong> inequalities simultaneously. The solution is the region where all shaded areas overlap. The SAT usually asks you to identify a point that is or isn't in this region.</div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — testing a point</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      System: <strong>y ≤ −x + 4</strong> and <strong>y ≥ 2x − 2</strong><br><br>
      Does (1, 2) satisfy the system?<br>
      <span class="fb-work">Test ineq 1: 2 ≤ −(1) + 4 → 2 ≤ 3 ✓</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Test ineq 2: 2 ≥ 2(1) − 2 → 2 ≥ 0 ✓</span><br>
      <span style="font-size:13px;color:#111;">Yes — (1, 2) satisfies both inequalities and is in the solution region.</span><br><br>
      Does (3, 3) satisfy the system?<br>
      <span class="fb-work">Test ineq 1: 3 ≤ −3 + 4 → 3 ≤ 1 ✗</span><br>
      <span style="font-size:13px;color:#111;">No — (3, 3) fails the first inequality and is outside the solution region.</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">The fastest SAT method: test the point directly</div><div class="tip-body">When asked which point lies in the solution region, substitute each answer choice into all the inequalities. The correct answer satisfies every inequality. No graphing required.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Dashed vs. solid — boundary inclusion</div><div class="tip-body">Strict inequalities (&lt;, &gt;) use dashed lines — boundary not included. Non-strict (≤, ≥) use solid lines — boundary included. The SAT tests this distinction in "which point is a solution" questions.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Word problems: write both constraints</div><div class="tip-body">SAT word problems with two conditions (budget limit AND minimum quantity, for example) require two inequalities. Write both before solving. The answer must satisfy both simultaneously.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Convert to slope-intercept to identify region</div><div class="tip-body">Before graphing, solve for y to get slope-intercept form. Then: y &gt; → above the line; y &lt; → below. This removes ambiguity about which side to shade.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="sec-title" style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">Practice questions</div>
<div class="q-tabs">
