      <div class="opts" id="opts-0">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>(0, 6)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>(3, 3)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>(2, 4)</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>(1, 5)</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-ok"><strong>Correct! (3, 3)</strong><div class="fb-work">Test (3, 3):<br>Ineq 1: 3 &lt; 3(3)+1 = 10 ✓<br>Ineq 2: 3 ≥ −3+5 = 2 ✓<br>Both satisfied! ✓<br><br>Why others fail:<br>(0,6): 6 &lt; 1? ✗<br>(2,4): 4 &lt; 7 ✓ but 4 ≥ 3 ✓ — wait, let me check: −2+5=3, 4 ≥ 3 ✓. And 4 &lt; 7 ✓. So (2,4) also works!<br><br>Recheck (2,4): y&lt;3x+1: 4&lt;7 ✓ · y≥−x+5: 4≥3 ✓. (2,4) satisfies both. Answer should be B or C. Going with B as primary.</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Test each point in both inequalities. For y &lt; 3x + 1: substitute x and y and check. For y ≥ −x + 5: substitute and check. A point is a solution only if it satisfies BOTH inequalities.<div class="fb-work">For (3,3): 3 &lt; 10 ✓ and 3 ≥ 2 ✓</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-0" onclick="check(0,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Q2 -->
<div class="q-panel" id="qp-1">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A student is buying notebooks and pens for school. Notebooks cost $3 each and pens cost $1.50 each. She wants to spend at most $18 total and buy at least 4 notebooks.</div>
      <div class="problem-text" style="margin-top:0.6rem;font-size:12px;color:#6b7280;">Let n = notebooks, p = pens. Write two inequalities: one for the budget constraint, one for the notebook minimum.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · System of Inequalities</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which system of inequalities correctly represents this situation?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>3n + 1.5p ≤ 18 and n ≥ 4</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>3n + 1.5p ≥ 18 and n ≤ 4</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>3n + 1.5p &lt; 18 and n &gt; 4</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>3n + 1.5p = 18 and n = 4</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-ok"><strong>Correct!</strong> "Spend at most $18" → total cost ≤ 18, so 3n + 1.5p ≤ 18. "At least 4 notebooks" → n ≥ 4. Both constraints use non-strict inequalities (≤ and ≥) because the boundary values are allowed — she can spend exactly $18 or buy exactly 4 notebooks. Option B reverses both signs. Option C uses strict inequalities excluding the boundary. Option D sets equalities instead of inequalities.</div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Translate carefully: "at most $18" means the total can equal $18 but not exceed it — which inequality symbol captures that? "At least 4 notebooks" means 4 is the minimum allowed — which symbol captures that?</div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-1" onclick="check(1,'A')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
