<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 3 · Lesson 3.6</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Inequalities — Advanced</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master absolute value equations and inequalities — one of the most frequently tested advanced algebra topics on the SAT — and learn the two-case method that solves every problem of this type.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">What absolute value means</div>
  <div class="body-text">The absolute value of a number is its <strong>distance from zero</strong> on the number line — always non-negative. |5| = 5 and |−5| = 5 because both are 5 units from zero.<br><br>This distance interpretation is the key to solving absolute value equations and inequalities: you must consider two cases — one where the expression inside is positive, and one where it is negative.</div>
  <div class="formula-box">
    <div class="formula">|x| = a &nbsp;→&nbsp; x = a &nbsp;OR&nbsp; x = −a</div>
    <div class="formula-sub">Always two cases. Always consider both.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Equations vs. inequalities — different rules</div>
  <div class="two-col">
    <div class="case-card" style="background:#F5F3FF;">
      <div class="case-title" style="color:#4C1D95;">Absolute value equation: |A| = b</div>
      <div class="case-rule" style="color:#6b7280;">Split into two equations. Solve each separately. Check both answers in the original.</div>
      <div class="case-ex">|2x − 3| = 7<br>Case 1: 2x − 3 = 7 → x = 5<br>Case 2: 2x − 3 = −7 → x = −2<br>Solutions: x = 5 or x = −2</div>
    </div>
    <div class="case-card" style="background:#EDE9FE;">
      <div class="case-title" style="color:#4C1D95;">|A| &lt; b → "AND" (between)</div>
      <div class="case-rule" style="color:#6b7280;">Less than → bounded solution. The expression is between −b and b simultaneously.</div>
      <div class="case-ex">|2x − 3| &lt; 7<br>−7 &lt; 2x − 3 &lt; 7<br>−4 &lt; 2x &lt; 10<br>−2 &lt; x &lt; 5</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="two-col" style="margin-top: 10px;">
    <div class="case-card" style="background:#FEF3C7;">
      <div class="case-title" style="color:#92400E;">|A| &gt; b → "OR" (outside)</div>
      <div class="case-rule" style="color:#6b7280;">Greater than → two separate solution regions. The expression is either very positive or very negative.</div>
      <div class="case-ex">|2x − 3| &gt; 7<br>Case 1: 2x − 3 &gt; 7 → x &gt; 5<br>Case 2: 2x − 3 &lt; −7 → x &lt; −2<br>Solution: x &lt; −2 or x &gt; 5</div>
    </div>
    <div class="case-card" style="background:#f9fafb;">
      <div class="case-title">Quick memory trick</div>
      <div class="case-rule" style="color:#6b7280;"><strong>Less than</strong> → <strong>AND</strong> → one connected interval (between two values)<br><br><strong>Greater than</strong> → <strong>OR</strong> → two separate rays (outside two values)</div>
      <div class="case-ex">"Less-and, great-or"</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Full worked example</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      Solve: <strong>|3x + 6| ≥ 12</strong><br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">This is |A| ≥ b → "OR" case (greater than or equal)</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Case 1: 3x + 6 ≥ 12 → 3x ≥ 6 → x ≥ 2</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Case 2: 3x + 6 ≤ −12 → 3x ≤ −18 → x ≤ −6</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Solution: x ≤ −6 or x ≥ 2</span><br><br>
      Check x = 3: |3(3)+6| = |15| = 15 ≥ 12 ✓<br>
      Check x = −7: |3(−7)+6| = |−15| = 15 ≥ 12 ✓<br>
      Check x = 0: |0+6| = 6 ≥ 12? ✗ (correctly excluded)
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="warn-box">
    <div class="warn-label">Critical rule — no solution case</div>
    <div class="warn-text">If b is negative, the equation |A| = b has <strong>no solution</strong> — absolute value is always ≥ 0, so it can never equal a negative number. Similarly, |A| &lt; −3 has no solution. The SAT tests this. Always check if b &lt; 0 before solving.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Isolate the absolute value first</div><div class="tip-body">Before splitting into cases, get the absolute value expression alone on one side. Don't split until |expression| = number is fully set up.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Check both solutions</div><div class="tip-body">After solving both cases of an equation, substitute each answer back into the original. Occasionally one solution is extraneous (doesn't actually satisfy the original).</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Less-than → compact interval</div><div class="tip-body">|x − a| &lt; d means x is within distance d of a: the solution is a − d &lt; x &lt; a + d. This interpretation is faster than algebraic splitting for simple problems.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Greater-than → two rays</div><div class="tip-body">|x − a| &gt; d means x is more than distance d away from a: x &lt; a − d or x &gt; a + d. Picture the number line — two arrows pointing outward.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="sec-title" style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">Practice questions</div>
<div class="q-tabs">
