<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 3 · Lesson 3.7</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Absolute Value</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Go deeper on absolute value — learn its key algebraic properties, how to evaluate and simplify expressions involving absolute value, and how the SAT uses it in multi-step problems.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>12 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Key properties of absolute value</div>
  <div class="body-text">Absolute value measures distance from zero — it is always non-negative. Beyond the basic definition, knowing these algebraic properties lets you simplify and evaluate expressions quickly.</div>
  <div class="formula-box">
    <div class="formula">
      |a| ≥ 0 &nbsp;&nbsp; for all real a<br>
      |a| = |−a| &nbsp;&nbsp; (symmetric)<br>
      |ab| = |a| · |b| &nbsp;&nbsp; (multiplicative)<br>
      |a + b| ≤ |a| + |b| &nbsp;&nbsp; (triangle inequality)
    </div>
    <div class="formula-sub">These hold for all real numbers a and b.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="prop-grid">
    <div class="prop-card">
      <div class="prop-title">|a²| = a² always</div>
      <div class="prop-rule">Since a² is always non-negative, the absolute value has no effect. This simplifies many expressions.</div>
      <div class="prop-ex">|x²| = x² &nbsp; (for any real x)<br>|x² − 4| ≠ x² − 4 &nbsp; (could be negative)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="prop-card">
      <div class="prop-title">√(x²) = |x|</div>
      <div class="prop-rule">The square root of x² is the absolute value of x — not x itself. This matters when x could be negative.</div>
      <div class="prop-ex">√(9) = 3 ✓<br>√(x²) = |x| ← not just x<br>If x = −4: √(16) = 4 = |−4| ✓</div>
    </div>
    <div class="prop-card">
      <div class="prop-title">|a/b| = |a|/|b| (b ≠ 0)</div>
      <div class="prop-rule">Absolute value distributes over multiplication and division — but NOT over addition or subtraction.</div>
      <div class="prop-ex">|−6/2| = |−3| = 3 ✓<br>|6|/|2| = 3 ✓ (same result)<br>|3 − 7| ≠ |3| − |7| ✗</div>
    </div>
    <div class="prop-card">
      <div class="prop-title">|a − b| = distance between a and b</div>
      <div class="prop-rule">The absolute value of a difference gives the distance between two points on a number line — regardless of order.</div>
      <div class="prop-ex">|3 − 8| = 5 (distance from 3 to 8)<br>|8 − 3| = 5 (same distance)<br>|x − 5| = 3 means x is 3 away from 5</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — multi-step absolute value</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      If |x − 3| = 5, what are the possible values of |x|?<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Step 1 — solve for x:</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">x − 3 = 5 → x = 8 &nbsp;OR&nbsp; x − 3 = −5 → x = −2</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Step 2 — evaluate |x| for each:</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">|8| = 8 &nbsp;OR&nbsp; |−2| = 2</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">So |x| = 8 or |x| = 2</span><br><br>
      Note: The SAT might ask for the sum or product of these values: 8 + 2 = 10, or 8 × 2 = 16.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="trap-box">
    <div class="trap-label">Most common absolute value mistake</div>
    <div class="trap-text"><strong>Removing absolute value bars incorrectly:</strong> Students often write |x + 3| = x + 3, forgetting that if x + 3 is negative, this is wrong. Never remove absolute value bars unless you know the sign of the expression inside. Always consider both cases.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Evaluate before simplifying</div><div class="tip-body">When given a specific value of x, substitute first, then apply the absolute value. Don't try to simplify the general expression — plug in numbers and evaluate.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">√(x²) = |x| — always</div><div class="tip-body">If the SAT asks to simplify √(x²) or √((x−3)²), the answer is |x| or |x−3|, not x or x−3. The square root is always non-negative.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Distance interpretation saves time</div><div class="tip-body">|x − a| = b means x is exactly b units from a. Instead of algebra, just add and subtract: x = a + b or x = a − b. Faster on simple problems.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Check if the expression inside can be negative</div><div class="tip-body">Before removing |bars|, ask: can the expression inside be negative for any valid x? If yes, keep the absolute value. If the expression is always non-negative (like x²), you can simplify.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

