<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 3 · Lesson 3.8</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Linear Functions & Slope</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Connect linear equations to function notation, master average rate of change from tables and graphs, and learn to recognize when the SAT is really asking about slope in disguise.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Functions vs. equations — what changes</div>
  <div class="body-text">A <strong>linear function</strong> is a linear equation written using function notation: f(x) instead of y. The notation f(x) emphasizes that the output depends on the input x — and allows the SAT to ask questions like "find f(3)" or "for what value of x does f(x) = 7?"</div>
  <div class="formula-box">
    <div class="formula">
      f(x) = mx + b<br>
      <span style="font-size:13px;font-weight:400;color:#6b7280;">f(x) is read "f of x" — the output when input is x</span>
    </div>
    <div class="formula-sub">m = slope (rate of change) · b = f(0) = y-intercept (initial value)</div>
  </div>
  <table class="concept-table">
    <tr><th>Concept</th><th>What it means</th><th>How to calculate</th></tr>
    <tr><td>f(a)</td><td>The output of the function when x = a</td><td>Substitute x = a into the equation and simplify</td></tr>
    <tr><td>f(a) = b</td><td>Find the input x that gives output b</td><td>Set mx + c = b and solve for x</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Slope m</td><td>Change in output per unit change in input</td><td><em>m = (f(x₂) − f(x₁)) / (x₂ − x₁)</em></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Average rate of change</td><td>The slope between two specific points</td><td>Same formula as slope — applied to any two points</td></tr>
    <tr><td>f(0)</td><td>The y-intercept — value when x = 0</td><td>Substitute x = 0, or read b directly from f(x) = mx + b</td></tr>
  </table>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Rate of change from a table</div>
  <div class="body-text">The SAT frequently gives a table of (x, y) or (x, f(x)) values and asks for the rate of change (slope) or a missing value. For a <strong>linear</strong> function, the rate of change is constant — so any two rows give the same slope.</div>
  <div class="two-col">
    <div class="mini-card">
      <div class="mini-title">Check linearity first</div>
      <div class="mini-body">For a table to represent a linear function, equal changes in x must produce equal changes in y. If Δx is constant and Δy is constant, the function is linear.</div>
      <div class="mini-ex">x: 0, 2, 4, 6<br>y: 3, 7, 11, 15<br>Δx = 2, Δy = 4 → slope = 4/2 = 2 ✓</div>
    </div>
    <div class="mini-card">
      <div class="mini-title">Find a missing value</div>
      <div class="mini-body">Once you have the slope, use point-slope or substitute into y = mx + b to find any missing value in the table.</div>
      <div class="mini-ex">slope = 2, passes through (0,3)<br>f(x) = 2x + 3<br>f(5) = 2(5) + 3 = 13</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — average rate of change</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      f(x) = 3x² − 2x + 1. Find the average rate of change from x = 1 to x = 4.<br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">f(1) = 3(1) − 2(1) + 1 = 2</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">f(4) = 3(16) − 2(4) + 1 = 48 − 8 + 1 = 41</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Average rate of change = (41 − 2)/(4 − 1) = 39/3 = 13</span><br><br>
      Note: For a linear function, the average rate of change equals the slope everywhere. For non-linear functions, it varies by interval.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">f(x) = k means solve for x</div><div class="tip-body">When the SAT asks "for what value of x does f(x) = 7?", that's just asking you to solve an equation. Set the function equal to 7 and solve — it's not asking for a function value.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Average rate of change = slope formula</div><div class="tip-body">The phrase "average rate of change" always means (f(b)−f(a))/(b−a). For a linear function this equals the slope. For any function, it's the slope of the secant line between two points.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Slope from a table: pick any two rows</div><div class="tip-body">For linear functions, every pair of rows gives the same slope. Pick the two rows with the cleanest numbers to minimize arithmetic errors.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">"Rate" in word problems = slope</div><div class="tip-body">Any word problem mentioning a constant rate — miles per hour, dollars per item, degrees per minute — is describing slope. Identify the unit rate and that's your m in f(x) = mx + b.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="sec-title" style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">Practice questions</div>
<div class="q-tabs">
