<!-- Q1 -->
<div class="q-panel active" id="qp-0">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A linear function f is defined by:</div>
      <span class="math-eq">f(x) = −3x + 11</span>
      <div class="hint">To find f(a), substitute a for x. To find where f(x) = k, set −3x + 11 = k and solve for x.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 1 · Function Notation</div>
      <div class="q-text">For what value of <strong>x</strong> does f(x) = −4?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-0">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>x = 3</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>x = 5</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>x = −5</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>x = 7</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-ok"><strong>Correct! x = 5</strong><div class="fb-work">f(x) = −4<br>−3x + 11 = −4<br>−3x = −15<br>x = 5<br>Check: f(5) = −3(5) + 11 = −15 + 11 = −4 ✓</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> "f(x) = −4" means set the function equal to −4 and solve for x. Replace f(x) with −4: −3x + 11 = −4, then solve.<div class="fb-work">−3x = −15 → x = 5</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-0" onclick="check(0,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Q2 -->
<div class="q-panel" id="qp-1">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">The table shows values of a linear function g.</div>
      <table class="data-table">
        <tr><th>x</th><th>g(x)</th></tr>
        <tr><td>1</td><td>5</td></tr>
        <tr><td>3</td><td>11</td></tr>
        <tr><td>5</td><td>17</td></tr>
        <tr><td>7</td><td>?</td></tr>
      </table>
      <div class="hint">Find the slope using any two rows. Then extend the pattern to find g(7). Alternatively, write the equation and substitute x = 7.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · Linear Functions from Tables</div>
      <div class="q-text">What is <strong>g(7)</strong>?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>20</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>21</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>23</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>25</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-ok"><strong>Correct! g(7) = 23</strong><div class="fb-work">Slope = (11 − 5)/(3 − 1) = 6/2 = 3<br>Using point (1, 5): g(x) = 3x + 2<br>g(7) = 3(7) + 2 = 21 + 2 = 23<br>Check: pattern adds 6 each time x increases by 2.<br>g(5)=17, g(7)=17+6=23 ✓</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Find the slope from any two rows — each time x increases by 2, g(x) increases by 6. So slope = 6/2 = 3. Write the equation g(x) = 3x + b, find b using any point, then evaluate at x = 7.<div class="fb-work">g(x) = 3x + 2 → g(7) = 23</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-1" onclick="check(1,'C')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Q3 -->
<div class="q-panel" id="qp-2">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">A car rental company charges a base fee of $25 plus $0.18 per mile driven. A competitor charges $40 flat with no mileage fee.</div>
      <div class="problem-text" style="margin-top:0.6rem;">Let C₁(m) = cost at Company 1 and C₂(m) = cost at Company 2, where m = miles driven.</div>
      <div class="hint">Write both as functions: C₁(m) = 25 + 0.18m and C₂(m) = 40. Find where the two functions are equal — that's the break-even mileage.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 3 · Linear Functions — Real World</div>
      <div class="q-text">At how many miles do both companies charge the <strong>same total cost</strong>?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-2">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>approximately 56 miles</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>approximately 83 miles</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>approximately 138 miles</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>approximately 222 miles</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-ok"><strong>Correct! ≈ 83 miles</strong><div class="fb-work">Set C₁(m) = C₂(m):<br>25 + 0.18m = 40<br>0.18m = 15<br>m = 15/0.18 = 83.3̄ miles<br><br>Below 83 miles → Company 2 is cheaper (flat fee)<br>Above 83 miles → Company 1 is cheaper (no flat fee)<br>At ≈ 83 miles → same cost ✓</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-2-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Set the two cost functions equal: 25 + 0.18m = 40. Solve for m by subtracting 25 from both sides, then dividing by 0.18.<div class="fb-work">0.18m = 15 → m = 15 ÷ 0.18 ≈ 83.3</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-2" onclick="check(2,'B')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

