<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 3 · Lesson 3.9</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Introduction to Quadratics</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Learn the standard form of a quadratic expression, master FOIL and the three special product patterns, and practice expanding and identifying quadratic expressions — the foundation for all quadratic solving.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>13 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">What is a quadratic?</div>
  <div class="body-text">A <strong>quadratic expression</strong> contains a variable raised to the second power as its highest degree term, written in standard form. Its graph is always a parabola.</div>
  <div class="formula-box">
    <div class="formula">ax² + bx + c</div>
    <div class="formula-sub">a ≠ 0 · a = leading coefficient · b = linear coefficient · c = constant (y-intercept)</div>
  </div>
  <div class="parts-grid">
    <div class="part-card">
      <div class="part-label">a — leading coefficient</div>
      <div class="part-body">Determines parabola direction and width. a &gt; 0 opens up; a &lt; 0 opens down.</div>
      <div class="part-ex">2x² + 3x + 1 → a = 2</div>
    </div>
    <div class="part-card">
      <div class="part-label">b — linear coefficient</div>
      <div class="part-body">Affects horizontal position of vertex. Axis of symmetry: x = −b/(2a).</div>
      <div class="part-ex">2x² + 3x + 1 → b = 3</div>
    </div>
    <div class="part-card">
      <div class="part-label">c — constant term</div>
      <div class="part-body">Equals the y-intercept — value when x = 0. Read directly from standard form.</div>
      <div class="part-ex">2x² + 3x + 1 → c = 1</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">The three special products — memorize these</div>
  <div class="products-grid">
    <div class="prod-card">
      <div class="prod-title">Perfect square — sum</div>
      <div class="prod-formula">(a + b)² = a² + 2ab + b²</div>
      <div class="prod-body">Middle term is always 2ab — the most frequently missed pattern.</div>
      <div class="prod-ex">(x + 5)² = x² + 10x + 25<br>(2x + 3)² = 4x² + 12x + 9</div>
    </div>
    <div class="prod-card">
      <div class="prod-title">Perfect square — difference</div>
      <div class="prod-formula">(a − b)² = a² − 2ab + b²</div>
      <div class="prod-body">Last term always positive. Middle term negative.</div>
      <div class="prod-ex">(x − 4)² = x² − 8x + 16<br>(3x − 1)² = 9x² − 6x + 1</div>
    </div>
    <div class="prod-card">
      <div class="prod-title">Difference of squares</div>
      <div class="prod-formula">(a + b)(a − b) = a² − b²</div>
      <div class="prod-body">Middle terms cancel. No linear term in the result.</div>
      <div class="prod-ex">(x + 7)(x − 7) = x² − 49<br>(2x + 3)(2x − 3) = 4x² − 9</div>
    </div>
    <div class="prod-card">
      <div class="prod-title">General FOIL</div>
      <div class="prod-formula">(x + p)(x + q) = x² + (p+q)x + pq</div>
      <div class="prod-body">Linear coefficient = sum of p, q. Constant = product of p, q.</div>
      <div class="prod-ex">(x + 3)(x + 5) = x² + 8x + 15<br>(x − 2)(x + 6) = x² + 4x − 12</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      Expand: <strong>(3x − 2)² − (x + 4)(x − 4)</strong><br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Part 1: (3x − 2)² = 9x² − 12x + 4</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Part 2: (x + 4)(x − 4) = x² − 16</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Result: (9x² − 12x + 4) − (x² − 16) = 8x² − 12x + 20</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Memorize the three special products</div><div class="tip-body">The SAT uses these constantly. Expanding (a+b)², (a−b)², and (a+b)(a−b) in 3 seconds without FOIL is a major time advantage on the no-calculator section.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">(a+b)² ≠ a² + b²</div><div class="tip-body">The most common quadratic mistake: forgetting the middle term. (x+3)² = x² + 6x + 9, NOT x² + 9. The middle term 2ab is always there in a perfect square.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">c is the y-intercept always</div><div class="tip-body">In ax² + bx + c, the constant c is the y-intercept. The SAT often asks for this — just read it directly without substituting x = 0.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Sum and product pattern for factoring</div><div class="tip-body">For x² + bx + c = (x+p)(x+q): p + q = b and p × q = c. Find two numbers that add to b and multiply to c — that's the foundation of factoring in Lesson 3.10.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="sec-title" style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">Practice questions</div>
<div class="q-tabs">
  <button class="q-tab active" onclick="switchQ(0,this)">Question 1</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(1,this)">Question 2</button>
  <button class="q-tab" onclick="switchQ(2,this)">Question 3</button>
</div>

<div class="q-panel active" id="qp-0">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">Expand the expression:</div>
      <span class="math-eq">(2x + 5)²</span>
      <div class="hint">Use (a + b)² = a² + 2ab + b² with a = 2x, b = 5. Middle term = 2·(2x)·5 = 20x. Don't forget it!</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 1 · Perfect Square</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which expression is equivalent to <strong>(2x + 5)²</strong>?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-0">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>4x² + 25</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>4x² + 10x + 25</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>4x² + 20x + 25</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(0,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>2x² + 20x + 25</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-ok"><strong>Correct! 4x² + 20x + 25</strong><div class="fb-work">(2x)² + 2·(2x)·5 + 5² = 4x² + 20x + 25<br>A forgets the middle term. B uses 2·5=10 instead of 20x. D squares 2x incorrectly as 2x² instead of 4x².</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-0-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Apply (a+b)² = a² + 2ab + b² with a=2x, b=5. (2x)² = 4x². Middle term: 2×(2x)×5 = 20x.<div class="fb-work">4x² + 20x + 25</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-0" onclick="check(0,'C')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<!-- Q2 -->
<div class="q-panel" id="qp-1">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">Simplify the expression:</div>
      <span class="math-eq">(x + 6)(x − 6) − (x − 3)²</span>
      <div class="hint">Use difference of squares for the first part: (x+6)(x−6) = x² − 36. Use perfect square for the second: (x−3)² = x² − 6x + 9. Then subtract carefully — watch the signs.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 2 · Special Products</div>
      <div class="q-text">Which expression is equivalent to <strong>(x + 6)(x − 6) − (x − 3)²</strong>?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-1">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>6x − 45</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>−27</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'C')"><span class="opt-l">C</span>6x − 27</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(1,this,'D')"><span class="opt-l">D</span>2x² − 6x − 45</div>
      </div>
      <div class="q-actions">
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-ok"><strong>Correct! 6x − 45</strong><div class="fb-work">(x+6)(x−6) = x² − 36<br>(x−3)² = x² − 6x + 9<br>Result: (x² − 36) − (x² − 6x + 9)<br>= x² − 36 − x² + 6x − 9<br>= 6x − 45 ✓<br>Note: x² terms cancel!</div></div>
        <div class="feedback" id="fb-1-fail"><strong>Not quite.</strong> Expand each part first: (x+6)(x−6) = x²−36 and (x−3)² = x²−6x+9. Then subtract the entire second expression — distribute the negative sign to every term inside.<div class="fb-work">x²−36 − x²+6x−9 = 6x−45</div></div>
        <button class="btn-check" id="btn-1" onclick="check(1,'A')" disabled>Check answer</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Q3 -->
<div class="q-panel" id="qp-2">
  <div class="math-layout">
    <div class="problem-panel">
      <div class="panel-label">Problem</div>
      <div class="problem-text">The expression x² + kx + 36 is a perfect square trinomial — it equals (x + n)² for some integer n.</div>
      <div class="hint">For a perfect square trinomial (x + n)² = x² + 2nx + n². The constant term is n², so n² = 36 → n = 6 or n = −6. The middle coefficient k = 2n.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="q-panel-inner">
      <div class="q-label">Question 3 · Perfect Square Identification</div>
      <div class="q-text">What are the possible values of <strong>k</strong>?</div>
      <div class="opts" id="opts-2">
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'A')"><span class="opt-l">A</span>k = 6 only</div>
        <div class="opt" onclick="pick(2,this,'B')"><span class="opt-l">B</span>k = 12 only</div>
