<div class="tag">SAT Math · Module 3 · Lesson 3.10</div>
<div class="lesson-title">Solving Quadratic Equations</div>
<div class="lesson-sub">Master the three methods for solving quadratic equations — factoring, the quadratic formula, and completing the square — and learn when to use each one for maximum speed on the SAT.</div>
<div class="dur-row"><span><b>14 min</b> read</span><span><b>3</b> practice questions</span><span><b>+20 pts</b> on completion</span></div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">Three methods — choose the fastest one</div>
  <div class="body-text">Every quadratic equation can be solved by any of these three methods. The SAT rewards students who pick the right method for the problem — the wrong method can waste 2–3 minutes.</div>
  <div class="method-grid">
    <div class="method-card" style="background:#F5F3FF;">
      <div class="method-title" style="color:#4C1D95;">Method 1 — Factoring</div>
      <div class="method-when" style="color:#6b7280;"><strong>Use when:</strong> the equation looks factorable (integer coefficients, small numbers). Always try this first — it's fastest.</div>
      <div class="method-steps">
        1. Set equation = 0<br>
        2. Factor into (x + p)(x + q) = 0<br>
        3. Set each factor = 0 and solve
      </div>
      <div class="method-ex">x² + 5x + 6 = 0<br>(x + 2)(x + 3) = 0<br>x = −2 or x = −3</div>
    </div>
    <div class="method-card" style="background:#EDE9FE;">
      <div class="method-title" style="color:#4C1D95;">Method 2 — Quadratic Formula</div>
      <div class="method-when" style="color:#6b7280;"><strong>Use when:</strong> the equation doesn't factor easily, or you need exact answers with radicals.</div>
      <div class="method-steps">
        Set ax² + bx + c = 0<br>
        Then apply the formula →
      </div>
      <div class="method-ex">Always works. Never fails.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="method-card" style="background:#f9fafb;">
      <div class="method-title">Method 3 — Square Root Method</div>
      <div class="method-when" style="color:#6b7280;"><strong>Use when:</strong> there's no linear term (no x, only x²). Isolate x² and take the square root of both sides.</div>
      <div class="method-steps">
        x² = k → x = ±√k
      </div>
      <div class="method-ex">4x² − 36 = 0<br>4x² = 36<br>x² = 9<br>x = ±3</div>
    </div>
    <div class="method-card" style="background:#EAF3DE;">
      <div class="method-title" style="color:#27500A;">SAT speed rule</div>
      <div class="method-when" style="color:#6b7280;">Try factoring first (5 sec). If it doesn't factor in 10 seconds, use the quadratic formula. Don't waste time trying to force a factorization.</div>
      <div class="method-steps" style="color:#374151;">Factoring → fastest when it works<br>Quadratic formula → always reliable<br>Square root → for x² = k only</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">The Quadratic Formula — and the discriminant</div>
  <div class="formula-box">
    <div class="formula">x = (−b ± √(b² − 4ac)) / 2a</div>
    <div class="formula-sub">for ax² + bx + c = 0, where a ≠ 0</div>
  </div>
  <div class="body-text">The expression under the square root, <strong>b² − 4ac</strong>, is called the <strong>discriminant</strong>. It tells you how many real solutions the equation has — without fully solving it.</div>
  <div class="discriminant-grid">
    <div class="disc-card" style="background:#EAF3DE;">
      <div class="disc-cond" style="color:#27500A;">b² − 4ac &gt; 0</div>
      <div class="disc-result" style="color:#3B6D11;"><strong>Two distinct real solutions</strong><br>Parabola crosses x-axis twice</div>
      <div class="disc-ex">x² − 5x + 4 = 0 → D = 9 &gt; 0 → x = 1 or x = 4</div>
    </div>
    <div class="disc-card" style="background:#EDE9FE;">
      <div class="disc-cond" style="color:#4C1D95;">b² − 4ac = 0</div>
      <div class="disc-result" style="color:#7C3AED;"><strong>One repeated real solution</strong><br>Parabola touches x-axis at vertex</div>
      <div class="disc-ex">x² − 6x + 9 = 0 → D = 0 → x = 3 only</div>
    </div>
    <div class="disc-card" style="background:#FCEBEB;">
      <div class="disc-cond" style="color:#A32D2D;">b² − 4ac &lt; 0</div>
      <div class="disc-result" style="color:#A32D2D;"><strong>No real solutions</strong><br>Parabola doesn't cross x-axis</div>
      <div class="disc-ex">x² + x + 1 = 0 → D = −3 &lt; 0 → no real solutions</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="example-box">
    <div class="example-label">Worked example — quadratic formula</div>
    <div class="example-text">
      Solve: <strong>2x² − 3x − 5 = 0</strong><br><br>
      <span class="fb-work">a = 2, b = −3, c = −5</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">Discriminant: (−3)² − 4(2)(−5) = 9 + 40 = 49</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">x = (3 ± √49) / 4 = (3 ± 7) / 4</span><br>
      <span class="fb-work">x = (3 + 7)/4 = 10/4 = 5/2 &nbsp;OR&nbsp; x = (3 − 7)/4 = −4/4 = −1</span><br>
      Check: 2(25/4) − 3(5/2) − 5 = 25/2 − 15/2 − 10/2 = 0 ✓
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card">
  <div class="sec-title">SAT strategy tips</div>
  <div class="tips-grid">
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Always set equation to zero first</div><div class="tip-body">Before factoring or using the formula, make sure the equation is in the form ax² + bx + c = 0. If the equation has terms on both sides, move everything to one side before doing anything else.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Use the discriminant for "how many solutions" questions</div><div class="tip-body">If the SAT asks how many real solutions an equation has — compute b² − 4ac. You don't need to fully solve it. Positive → 2 solutions. Zero → 1 solution. Negative → 0 solutions.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Factoring: find two numbers that multiply to c and add to b</div><div class="tip-body">For x² + bx + c = 0: find p and q such that p × q = c and p + q = b. Then factor as (x + p)(x + q) = 0. This is faster to execute than the formula for clean integer roots.</div></div>
    <div class="tip"><div class="tip-title">Sum and product of roots</div><div class="tip-body">For ax² + bx + c = 0 with roots r₁ and r₂: sum of roots = −b/a and product of roots = c/a. The SAT occasionally asks for the sum or product of roots without asking you to find each root.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

